# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: switzerland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:switzerland/11th-meridian-east] The **meridian 11° east of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, Europe, Africa, the Atlantic Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:switzerland/11th-meridian-east] The 11th meridian east forms a great circle with the 169th meridian west.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] The **1928 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **II Olympic Winter Games** (French: *IIes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*; German: *II.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*; Italian: *II Giochi olimpici invernali*; Romansh: *II Gieus olimpics d'enviern*) and commonly known as **St.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Moritz 1928** (French: *Saint-Moritz 1928*; Romansh: *San Murezzan 1928*), were an international winter multi-sport event that was celebrated from 11 to 19 February 1928 in St.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] The 1928 Games were the first true Winter Olympics to be held as a stand-alone event, not in conjunction with a Summer Olympics.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] The preceding 1924 Winter Games were retroactively renamed the inaugural Winter Olympics, although they had in fact been organised alongside the 1924 Summer Olympics in France.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Before 1924, the winter events were included in the schedule of the Summer Games and there were no separate Winter Games.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] The 1928 Winter Games also replaced the now redundant Nordic Games, which had been held at varying intervals since early in the 20th century.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] The hosts were challenged by fluctuating weather conditions; the opening ceremony was held in a blizzard, while warm weather conditions plagued sporting events throughout the rest of the Games.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] The 10,000 metre speed-skating event was controversially abandoned and officially cancelled.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Filmed footage of the games exists in a silent, feature-length documentary, *The White Stadium*.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 14 events contested in 4 sports (8 disciplines).
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Athletes from 25 nations competed at these Games, up from 16 in 1924.
[src:switzerland/1928-winter-olympics] Nations making their first appearance at the Winter Olympic Games were Argentina (first participation of a delegation coming from a country belonging to the Southern Hemisphere), Estonia, Germany, Japan, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Mexico, the Netherlands, and Romania.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The **1948 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **V Olympic Winter Games** (German: *V.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*; French: *Ves Jeux olympiques d'hiver*; Italian: *V Giochi olimpici invernali*; Romansh: *V Gieus olimpics d'enviern*) and commonly known as **St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz 1948** (French: *Saint-Moritz 1948*; Romansh: *San Murezzan 1948*), were a winter multi-sport event held from 30 January to 8 February 1948 in St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Games were the first to be celebrated after World War II; it had been twelve years since the last Winter Games in 1936.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It was the first Winter Olympics held during the Cold War.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] From the selection of a host city in a neutral country to the exclusion of Japan and Germany, the political atmosphere of the post-war world was inescapable during the 1948 Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The organizing committee faced several challenges due to the lack of financial and human resources consumed by the war.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] These were the first of two winter Olympic Games under the IOC presidency of Sigfrid Edström.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] 28 nations marched in the opening ceremonies on 30 January 1948.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Bibi Torriani played for the Switzerland men's national ice hockey team and became the first ice hockey player to recite the Olympic Oath on behalf of all athletes.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Nearly 670 athletes competed in 22 events in four sports.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The 1948 Games also featured two demonstration sports: military patrol, which later became the biathlon, and winter pentathlon, which was discontinued after these Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Notable performances were turned in by figure skaters Dick Button and Barbara Ann Scott and skier Henri Oreiller.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Most athletic venues have existed since St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz first hosted the Winter Games in 1928.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] All the venues were outdoors, meaning the Games were heavily dependent on favorable weather conditions.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz to host the 1948 Games by acclamation at the 39th general session in Lausanne, Switzerland, on 6 September 1946.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The selection process consisted of two bids, and saw St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz be selected ahead of Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz was chosen because all of the venues of the 1928 Winter Olympics were available, and the Swiss resort could organize the Games much quicker than any other city except for 1936 host Garmisch-Partenkirchen which was not considered.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Despite the existence of many of the 1928 sites, it was still a difficult task to organize a Winter Olympic Games in less than 18 months.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Comité Olympique (CO) was composed of local dignitaries and members of the Swiss National Olympic Committee (COS).
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] They decided to separate into several sub-committees responsible for various aspects of the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] These committees included housing and maintenance, venue construction, finances, and media and advertising.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The local committees worked very closely with the Swiss federal government and the IOC to ensure that the organization of the Games proceeded without hindrance.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Since no athletes' village existed from the previous Games, the athletes and officials were housed in hotels around the city.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It was essential for the committees to draw upon their experiences from the 1928 Olympics.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Their selection of locations for the various events was contingent on the weather conditions, as all the events were held outdoors.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Over 800 people were involved in reporting the news of the Games to the world.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Nearly 500 press credentials were issued by the Press Commission for the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Television would not make its Olympic debut until 1956.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The coverage of the 1948 Games was split between newspapers and radio broadcasts.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The organizing committee had to provide technology, such as long-distance telephone lines and telegraph services, to assist the press in communicating with their constituents.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Over 2,200 people were needed to provide all the services for the press, officials, and athletes at the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] These services included sanitation, security, and care of the venues.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Accommodating the influx of people into St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz was difficult for the organizing committee.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It was complicated by the mountainous region in which the community was situated.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] A massive project to improve the village's transportation infrastructure had to be completed before the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] This included building and widening roads for vehicular traffic.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Several train stations were built to accommodate the increased demands for public transit.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] They also had to increase the capacity of the city's sewers.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] All of the projects had to be approved by the Swiss government and justified by its impact on the success of the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] To aid the organizing committee, the IOC demanded that all participating nations provide lists of their athletes several months before the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Consequently, the Swiss knew exactly how many athletes and officials to plan for.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Since these Games were the first since World War II, they were named "The Games of Renewal".
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Japan and Germany were not invited to these Games because the international community still ostracized them for their role in World War II.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Their absence was short-lived, though, as they returned to Olympic competition in 1952.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union did not send athletes to the St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz Games of 1948, but they did send ten delegates as observers of the Games to determine how successful the Soviet athletes would have been had they competed.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Sapporo, Japan had been the choice for the 1940 Winter Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] In 1938, the Japanese decided to decline the invitation to host the Games claiming that preparations for the Olympic Games were draining the country's resources.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The IOC turned to the host of the 1936 Games, Garmisch-Partenkirchen, which would make it the only city to host consecutive Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] This became impractical when Germany invaded Poland on 1 September 1939; subsequently Germany withdrew its bid to host the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Finland believed it could host the Games and extended an invitation to the IOC, but the Soviet Union's invasion of Finland ended all hope of an Olympic Games in 1940.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The 1944 Winter Olympics had been awarded to Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy in 1939.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] As the war continued, this proved impractical, and the second consecutive olympiad passed without celebrating the Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The IOC was presented with two possible host cities for the first post-war Games: Lake Placid, United States and St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The IOC decided to award the Games to Switzerland, a neutral country immediately following World War II, to avoid political posturing by former combatants.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The impact of World War II was still being felt in 1948.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The lack of financial resources and human energy made the organization of the Games challenging.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Athletes were also affected by a lack of resources.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Many competitors arrived with little or no equipment.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] In one notable case, Norwegian skiers had to borrow skis from the American team to compete.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 22 events contested in 4 sports (9 disciplines).
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] There were also two demonstration sports, military patrol and the winter pentathlon.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Two sliding sports were contested at the 1948 Winter Games; the first was bobsled.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] A controversy erupted when it was alleged that the sleds of the United States team had been sabotaged.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It was discovered that the steering wheels had been damaged.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] After news broke of the apparent improprieties a truck driver stepped forward and admitted to having accidentally backed into the shed housing the bobsleds.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The accident, however, did not hinder the United States teams, who won a bronze in the two-man event and a gold and a bronze in the four-man event.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Swiss two-man teams placed first and second, which is the best possible result for the event since only two teams were allowed to enter.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The driver of the first place team, Felix Endrich, beat his coach, the driver of the second place team, Fritz Feierabend.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The ice hockey tournament was won by Canada, with Czechoslovakia second and Switzerland third.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] This was the fifth Olympic gold medal for Canada in hockey.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The only team to beat Canada since hockey was introduced at the 1920 Summer Olympics was Great Britain at the 1936 Winter Olympics.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The tournament was almost canceled when rival teams representing the United States arrived.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] An Amateur Athletic Union (AAU) team was supported by the United States Olympic Committee (USOC), and an Amateur Hockey Association (AHA) team was supported by the Ligue Internationale de Hockey sur Glace (LIHG).
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The International Olympic Committee ruled that neither team could compete.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Still, the Swiss organizing committee allowed the AAU team to march in the opening ceremony and the AHA team to play unofficially without being eligible for medals.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Barbara Ann Scott became the first and only Canadian woman to win an Olympic gold medal in figure skating when she won the competition at St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Despite the distraction caused by a low-flying airplane during her compulsory routine, she could muster the focus to place first entering the free skate.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The ice had been shredded the night before the free skate by two ice hockey games (the ice resurfacer had not yet been invented); nonetheless, she was able to adjust her routine to avoid the potholes and emerge victorious.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Eighteen-year-old American Dick Button completed the unprecedented North American sweep of the figure skating gold medals.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] He led the field after the compulsory skate and won the gold medal by becoming the first person to complete a double Axel in competition.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Later in the 1952 Olympics, Dick Button would win gold a second time.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Swiss world champion Hans Gerschwiler fell during the free skate, but rebounded to win the silver medal.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The speed skating competition was held on the same rink that had hosted the events in 1928.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] At 1,856 m (6,089 ft) above sea level, the speed skating competition was held at the second-highest altitude in Olympic history; only Squaw Valley in 1960 was higher.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The competition was dominated by the Scandinavian countries of Norway and Sweden who won nine out of the twelve possible medals.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Scandinavians had done poorly in speed skating events up until the 1948 Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Their success was because speed skating in Europe had reached a standstill during World War II.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Only countries that were ancillary to the conflict had the resources to keep their speed skating programs intact.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The 500 meter race was won by Finn Helgesen of Norway.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] There was a three-way tie for second place between Norwegian Thomas Byberg and Americans Robert Fitzgerald and Kenneth Bartholomew.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] All three had finished in exactly 43.2 seconds.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Swede Åke Seyffarth won a gold medal in the 10,000 meter race and a silver medal in the 1,500 meter race.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The 5,000 meter event was affected by weather.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The twenty racers encountered wind, sun, and snow during the day's competition.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Finally, long-distance specialist Reidar Liaklev from Norway prevailed.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Alpine skiing made its Olympic debut at these Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] A few events had been held at the 1936 Games, but the St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz Games featured a full slate of three men's and three women's alpine events.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Frenchman Henri Oreiller won a medal in all three Alpine events: gold in the downhill and combined, and bronze in the slalom.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] He was one of only two athletes to win two gold medals at the 1948 Games, and he was also the only athlete to win three or more medals.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Austria dominated the women's alpine events, winning five out of nine possible medals.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Trude Beiser was a double-medal winner, earning gold in the combined event and silver in the downhill.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] She was not the only female skier to win two medals, though United States skier Gretchen Fraser won gold in the slalom and took silver behind Beiser in the combined.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Austrian Erika Mahringer earned two medals by winning bronze medals in both the slalom and the combined.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] In cross-country skiing, 106 skiers from 15 nations competed in three events.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The events were the 50 kilometer race, the 18 kilometer race, and the 4 x 10 kilometer relay.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] There were no women's events at the 1948 Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Martin Lundström of Sweden was the other athlete to win two gold medals when he won the 18 kilometer race and participated on the winning cross-country relay team.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Sweden won seven out of fifteen possible medals in the Nordic events, including all three gold medals and a sweep of the 18 kilometer race.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] All fifteen medals were won by either Sweden, Norway, or Finland.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Skeleton made its second appearance at the Olympics during these Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Skeleton was a form of luge that had originally appeared in the St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz region at the end of the 19th century.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] American John Heaton won his second Olympic medal in the skeleton; he won his first 20 years earlier when he was 19 years old.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Italian slider Nino Bibbia won the gold medal.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It was the first of his 231 career wins on the Cresta Boblsed track.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] One of the curves at Cesana Pariol, where the bobsled, luge, and skeleton events took place at the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin, was named after Bibbia.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Nordic combined event had been contested at each Winter Olympics since 1924.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Nordic combined required athletes to first compete in the open 18 kilometer cross-country ski race alongside the other cross-country competitors.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Their times would be assigned a point value.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The athletes would take two jumps off the ski jump hill two days later.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The jumps would be given a point value, and the longest jump would be combined with their cross-country time to create a score.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Traditional Nordic combined power Norway was stunned at the 1948 Games when Finland's Heikki Hasu became the first non-Norwegian to win the event.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Hasu's teammate Martti Huhtala took the silver, and Sven Israelsson from Sweden won the bronze.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Norwegians swept the ski jumping event.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Birger Ruud had won the gold medal in the ski jumping event at both the 1932 and 1936 Winter Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The twelve-year hiatus due to World War II meant that Ruud was 36 years old in 1948.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] He had retired from competition and was coaching the Norwegian team.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] However, when he arrived at the Games, he decided to come out of retirement and compete one last time.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Despite not having competed for several years, he earned a silver medal.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Norwegian Petter Hugsted won the gold and teammate Thorleif Schjelderup won the bronze.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Two demonstration sports were held at the 1948 Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Military patrol had been a demonstration sport at the 1924, 1928, and 1936 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It entailed a combination of cross-country skiing and shooting at targets.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Eventually the competition would be renamed Biathlon and was made an official Olympic medal sport at the 1960 Games in Squaw Valley, United States.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Winter pentathlon involved five competitions: 10 kilometer cross-country ski race, shooting, downhill skiing, fencing and horseback riding.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] This was the first and last time the event was held.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Fourteen competitors took part in the event.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The opening ceremonies were held at 10:00 am on 30 January, along with the initial hockey games and the first two runs of the two-man bobsled.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The closing ceremonies were held at 4:00 pm on 8 February.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] All of the medals were awarded at the closing ceremonies rather than immediately after the event, as current tradition dictates.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The Stad Olympique (Olympic Stadium) hosted the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The stadium was also used for speed skating, the figure skating competition, and the medal games for ice hockey.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Most of the ice hockey games were held at the *Suvretta* and *Kulm* stadiums in St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Skeleton was contested on the Cresta Run track.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Olympia Bob Run was built in 1897 and modernized for the 1948 Games, while the Cresta Run was first constructed in 1885.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The ski jump competitions were held at Olympiaschanze ski jump hill in St.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] It was built in 1927 for the 1928 Games and remained in use until 2006.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] The alpine events were held on ski-runs in and around Piz Nair.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Moritz, the same number as the previous Winter Games in 1936.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Chile, Denmark, Iceland, Korea, and Lebanon all made their Winter Olympic debut at these Games.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Germany and Japan were not invited because of their involvement in World War II.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Despite being an Axis power, Italy was allowed to send athletes after it defected to the Allies in 1943.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania had been annexed by the Soviet Union in 1940 and would not compete again as independent nations until 1992.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] Argentina returned to the Winter Games after missing the 1932 and 1936 Games, and Australia and Luxembourg did not compete in 1948, even though they had participated in 1936.
[src:switzerland/1948-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1948 Winter Games.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The **1954 FIFA World Cup** was the fifth edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial international football tournament for senior men's national teams of the nations affiliated to FIFA.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] It was held in Switzerland from 16 June to 4 July.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Switzerland was selected as the host country in July 1946.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] At the tournament, several all-time records for goalscoring were set, including the highest average number of goals scored per game.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The tournament was won by West Germany, who defeated tournament favourites Hungary 3–2 in the final for their first World Cup title.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay, the defending champions, were eliminated by Hungary in the semifinals and would lose to Austria in the match for third place.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The highest scoring match of a men’s World Cup happened in the quarterfinals of this tournament, when Austria defeated hosts Switzerland 7–5.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 12 goals of that match have never been surpassed in a World Cup since.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] As of 2026, this is the last World Cup to not have a goalless draw.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Switzerland was awarded the tournament unopposed at a meeting in Luxembourg City on 22 July 1946, the same day Brazil was selected to host the 1950 World Cup.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The hosts (Switzerland) and the defending champions (Uruguay) qualified automatically.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Of the remaining 14 places, 11 were allocated to Europe (including Egypt, Turkey, and Israel), two to the Americas, and one to Asia.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Scotland, Turkey, and South Korea made their World Cup debuts at this tournament (Turkey and Scotland had qualified for the 1950 competition but both withdrew).
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] South Korea became the first independent Asian country to participate in a World Cup tournament.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Austria appeared following a hiatus from 1934.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Several teams, such as Hungary and Czechoslovakia were back into the tournament after missing out the 1950 World Cup.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] German teams as well as Japan were allowed to qualify again, after having been banned from the 1950 FIFA World Cup.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany qualified against fellow Germans from the Saarland (which then was a French protectorate), while East Germany did not enter, having cancelled international football matches after the East German uprising of 1953.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Argentina declined to participate for the third successive World Cup.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 1954 tournament used a unique format.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The sixteen qualified teams were divided into four groups of four teams each.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Each group contained two seeded teams and two unseeded teams.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Only four matches were scheduled for each group, each pitting a seeded team against an unseeded team.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] This contrasts with the usual round-robin in which every team plays every other team: six matches in each group.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Another oddity was that extra time, which in most tournaments is not employed at the group stage, was played in the group games if the score was level after 90 minutes, with the result being a draw if the scores were still level after 120 minutes.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Two points were awarded for a win and one for a draw.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The two teams with the most points from each group progressed to the knockout stage.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the case of a tie between two teams for second place, the two tied teams competed in a play-off to decide which team would progress to the next stage, with extra time and drawing of lots if necessary.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Two of the four groups ended up requiring play-offs – one between Switzerland and Italy, and the other between Turkey and West Germany.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In each match, the unseeded team (Switzerland and West Germany) repeated an earlier victory against the seeded team (Italy and Turkey) to progress.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The fact that two group matches were played twice, while other group opponents never faced each other at all, attracted criticism; newly elected FIFA President Rodolphe Seeldrayers declared that this group format would be abandoned in future world cups.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] For each of the first two quarterfinals, one team progressing from group 1 was drawn against one team progressing from group 2.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the remaining two quarterfinals, this procedure was repeated for groups 3 and 4.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Before the tournament, it was stated that in the event of a quarterfinal being tied after 90 minutes, 30 minutes of extra time would be played, followed by drawing of lots if necessary.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Later, it was stated that a quarterfinal could be replayed in this situation.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The draw was scheduled to be held on Sunday 20 June, though in fact it was delayed into the early morning of Monday 21 June.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the semifinals, a further draw was held, with each semifinal featuring one team from groups 1–2 against one team from groups 3–4.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the event of a semifinal being tied after extra time, it would be replayed once, followed by drawing of lots if necessary.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The draw for the semifinals, held on Sunday 27 June, was delayed by a complaint from the Hungarian team concerning the manner in which their quarterfinal against Brazil had been played.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The final would be replayed if scores were level after extra-time.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] If the replay was also tied, the winner would be decided by the tournament organising committee, or by drawing of lots.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Before qualification was complete, the eight seeded teams were determined by FIFA.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] They were Austria, Brazil, England, France, Hungary, Italy, Spain, and Uruguay.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] These seedings were thrown into disarray when, in an unexpected result, Turkey eliminated Spain in qualification.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] FIFA resolved this situation by giving Turkey the seeding that had previously been allocated to Spain.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The Germany national football team, then limited to the area of West Germany only, had been reinstated as full FIFA members only in late 1950, had played only 18 games since, and were unseeded.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] When meeting the seeded Turkish side at Wankdorf stadium in Berne, the Turks scored early, but the Germans convincingly won the encounter, which would turn out as the first of two within six days.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The South Koreans, the other unseeded team, lost 7–0 and 9–0 against the seeded sides of Hungary and Turkey.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany, being denied the chance to play such an easy opponent, had to face the seeded team of Hungary, a favourite to win the World Cup.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Sepp Herberger, the West German coach, did not want his A-squad to suffer a possible defeat against a strong opponent while trying to qualify for a rather meaningless first place, and gambled by going the easier route into the play-offs and sending in a reserve side which lost 8–3 in Basel.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] A benefit was that the Hungarians did not get to know the best German players in case both teams would meet again - which they did, in the final, along with referee William Ling.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Now two teams were tied for second place on 2 points, and with no tie breaking procedures in effect, even though West Germany had beaten Turkey head-to-head, they had to play-off against each other, a match-up that West Germany easily won for the second time within six days, this time in Zürich.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungary's team captain Ferenc Puskás, considered by many as the best player in the world in that time, was injured by West German defender Werner Liebrich, and had to miss Hungary's next two matches.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Puskás played for Hungary in the final, despite still being in a questionable condition.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the quarterfinals, the favourites Hungary beat Brazil 4–2 in one of the most violent matches in football history, which became infamous as the Battle of Berne.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, the World Cup holders Uruguay sent England out of the tournament, also by 4–2.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] West Germany dispatched Yugoslavia 2–0, and Austria beat the host nation Switzerland in the game with the most goals in any World Cup match, 7–5.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the first semifinal, West Germany beat Austria 6–1.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In the other semifinal, one of the most exciting games of the tournament, Hungary led Uruguay 1–0 at halftime, but the game went to extra time with a 2–2 score after 90 minutes.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The deadlock was broken by Sándor Kocsis with two late goals to take Hungary through to the final, with Uruguay finally losing their unbeaten record in World Cup Final matches.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Uruguay then went on to be beaten for a second time as Austria secured third place.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] At the Wankdorf Stadion in Berne, 60,000 people watched the final between West Germany and Hungary, a rematch of a first-round game, which Hungary had won 8–3 against the reserves of the German team.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The Golden Team of the Hungarians were favourites, as they were unbeaten for a record of 32 consecutive matches, but they had had two tough knockout matches.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] It started raining on match day–in Germany this was dubbed *Fritz-Walter-Wetter* ("Fritz Walter's weather") because the West German team captain Fritz Walter was said to play his best in the rain, a result of having contracted malaria during the war.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Adi Dassler of *Adidas* provided the West German team with a new kind of shoes, with exchangeable studs that were replaced during halftime.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungary's Ferenc Puskás played again in the final, even though he was not fully fit.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Despite this he put his team ahead after only six minutes and with Zoltán Czibor adding another two minutes later it seemed that the pre-tournament favourites would take the title.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] However, with a quick goal from Max Morlock in the 10th minute and an equaliser by Helmut Rahn in the 19th, the tide began to turn.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The second half featured telling misses by the Hungarian team.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Barely six minutes before the end of the match, the popular German radio reporter Herbert Zimmermann delivered the most famous line in the German commentary, recommending that "Rahn should shoot from deep", which he did.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The second goal from Rahn gave West Germany a 3–2 lead while the Hungarian reporter György Szepesi burst into tears.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Later, Zimmermann called Puskás offside before he kicked the ball into Toni Turek's net with 2 minutes left.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] While referee William Ling pointed to the centre spot, linesman Griffiths signalled offside.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] After a one-minute consultation, Ling disallowed the claimed equaliser.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In Germany the success is known as the "Miracle of Bern" (*Das Wunder Von Bern*), and was memorialised in a 2003 film of the same name.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] For the Hungarians, the defeat was a disaster, and remains controversial for apparent refereeing errors and claims of doping.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] One controversy concerns the 2–2 equaliser.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Hungarian goalie Gyula Grosics jumped to catch Fritz Walter's corner shot, but Hans Schäfer obstructed him (in plain sight of TV cameras), allowing the ball to reach Rahn, who then scored.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Another controversy concerns allegations of doping.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Though teammates steadfastly denied this rumour, German historian Guido Knopp claimed in a 2004 documentary for German public channel ZDF that the players were injected with shots of vitamin C at half-time, using a needle earlier taken from a Soviet sports doctor.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] This resulted in both the better condition of the West German team in the second half and the wave of jaundice among their players following the tournament.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] A Leipzig University study in 2010 posited that the West German players had been injected with the banned substance methamphetamine.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Most controversial was the offside ruling for Puskás's intended 87th-minute equaliser.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The camera filming the official footage was in a bad position to judge the situation, but eyewitnesses claimed that the referee was wrong, including West German substitute player Alfred Pfaff.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In 2004, North German regional public channel NDR aired unofficial footage appearing to show that Puskás was onside.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Six venues in six cities (1 venue in each city) hosted the tournament's 26 matches.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Jakob Stadium in Basel, which hosted 6 matches.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The venues in Bern, Zurich and Lausanne each hosted 5 matches, the venue in Geneva hosted 4 matches, and the venue in Lugano only hosted 1 match.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] The 16 finalists named squads of 22 for the finals, though South Korea only named 20 players in their squad.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Unlike recent tournaments, there were no requirements for teams to name three goalkeepers; most teams did, but 6 did not.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Some teams also chose to leave some of their named squad at home, only bringing them to Switzerland if necessary.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] All times listed are local time (CET, UTC+1).
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] With 11 goals, Sándor Kocsis was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In total, 140 goals were scored by 63 players, with four of them credited as own goals.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:switzerland/1954-fifa-world-cup] Sönke Wortmann's 2003 German box-office hit *The Miracle of Bern* (in German: *Das Wunder von Bern*) re-tells the story of the German team's route to victory through the eyes of a young boy who admires the key player of the final, Helmut Rahn.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] On 11 June 1955, a multi-vehicle collision occurred during the 1955 24 Hours of Le Mans in Sarthe, France, resulting in the deaths of an estimated 82 to 84 people.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The disaster occurred at the Circuit de la Sarthe, when a mid-race collision sent Mercedes driver Pierre Levegh and his car into a spectator arena, causing his car to disintegrate and throwing him onto the racetrack, killing him instantly.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Debris from the car and the arena flew into the crowd, killing at least 82 people.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The disaster is the deadliest event in motorsport history, prompting multiple European countries to ban motorsports entirely; Switzerland did not officially lift its ban until 2026.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The cause of the crash was later determined to have been due to aggressive braking from Jaguar driver Mike Hawthorn.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Preparing for his pit stop, he pulled to the right side of the track in front of Austin-Healey driver Lance Macklin and abruptly braked.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Macklin swerved out from behind Hawthorn into the path of Levegh, who was passing on the left in his much faster Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Levegh rear-ended Macklin at high speed, the impact launching his own car through the air.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Levegh's car skipped over a protective earthen berm at 200 km/h (125 mph) and made at least two impacts within the spectator area, the last of which caused the car to disintegrate, throwing Levegh onto the track.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Large pieces of debris, including the Mercedes' engine block, radiator, front suspension, and bonnet (hood), were sent flying into the packed spectator area in front of the grandstand.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The rear of Levegh's car landed on the berm and exploded into flames.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] There was much debate over blame for the disaster.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The official inquiry held none of the drivers specifically responsible, but criticized the layout of the 30-year-old track, which had not been designed for cars as fast as those involved in the crash.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] There was great anticipation for the 1955 24 Hours of Le Mans, as Ferrari, Jaguar, and Mercedes-Benz had all won the race previously and all three automakers had arrived with new and improved cars.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The Ferraris, current champions at the time, were known to be fast but fragile and prone to mechanical failure.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Jaguar concentrated their racing almost exclusively on Le Mans and had an experienced driver lineup including Formula 1 Ferrari driver Mike Hawthorn.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] After gaining success in F1, Mercedes-Benz had debuted its new 300 SLR in that year's World Sportscar Championship, including a record-setting win at the Mille Miglia for Stirling Moss.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The 300 SLR featured a body made of an ultra-lightweight magnesium alloy called Elektron.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The car lacked the more effective state-of-the-art disc brakes featured on the rival Jaguar D-Type, instead incorporating inboard drum brakes and a large air brake behind the driver that could be raised to increase drag and slow the car.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] It had been Levegh's unprecedented solo drive in the 1952 race that failed in the last hour, which allowed Mercedes-Benz their first Le Mans victory.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Aside from two layout changes to make the circuit shorter, the Circuit de la Sarthe was largely unaltered since the inception of the race in 1923, when top speeds of cars were typically in the region of 100 km/h (60 mph).
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] By 1955, top speeds for the leading cars were over 270 km/h (170 mph).
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The circuit had been resurfaced and widened after the Second World War.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The pits and grandstands had been reconstructed, but there were no barriers between the pit lane and the racing line, and only a 1.2 m (4 ft) earthen bank between the track and the spectators.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The cars had no seat belts; the drivers reasoned that it was preferable to be thrown clear in a collision rather than be crushed or trapped in a burning car.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The 1955 race began at 4 pm on Saturday, and the lead cars of Eugenio Castellotti (Ferrari), Hawthorn (Jaguar), and Fangio (Mercedes-Benz) were at the head of the field in the first hour.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The other team cars were being kept on tighter leashes to conserve the cars, but still racing in the top ten.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Going into the second hour, Castellotti started dropping back, but Hawthorn and Fangio continued the duel, swapping the lead and dropping the lap record further, lapping most of the field.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The accident happened at 6:26 pm, at the end of lap 35, when the first pit stops for the leading cars began.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] On lap 35, Hawthorn and Fangio were still racing for the lead.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The lap before, Hawthorn's pit crew had signalled for him to come in the next lap.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] He had just lapped Levegh, who was running sixth, after the corner Arnage, and was determined to keep Fangio at bay for as long as he could.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Coming out of the Maison Blanche portion of the course, he rapidly caught up to Lance Macklin in his Austin Healey 100S, who had seen him and moved over to the right to let him pass.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Putting another lap on Macklin coming up to the main straight, Hawthorn then raised his hand to indicate he was pitting and pulled across to the right, and using the Jaguar's advanced disc brakes, braked hard enough to rapidly slow his Jaguar from his racing speed, catching Macklin out.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] There were two key factors regarding the track layout at that time.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] There was no designated deceleration lane for cars coming into the pits, and just before the main straight, there was a very slight right-hand kink in the road just after which Hawthorn started braking.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Macklin, who also braked hard, ran off the right-hand edge of the track, throwing up dust.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Noticing that Hawthorn was slowing down, Macklin swerved left to avoid Hawthorn.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] As a result, Macklin's car veered across to the centre of the track, briefly out of control.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] This put him into the way of Levegh's Mercedes, closing in at over 200 km/h (120 mph), intent on doing another lap and in front of Fangio, who was waiting to pass.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Levegh had no time to evade and, as he was about to collide, raised his hand to warn Fangio, who subsequently squeezed through the carnage and brushed Hawthorn's then-stationary Jaguar in the pits, allowing him to pass unscathed.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Levegh's front-right wheel rode up the rear-left of Macklin's car, which acted as a ramp and launched Levegh's car into the air, flying over spectators and rolling end over end for 80 metres (260 ft).
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Levegh was thrown out of his tumbling car and hit the ground, crushing his skull upon impact and killing him instantly.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The critical kink in the road put the car on a direct trajectory toward the packed terraces and grandstand.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The car landed on the earthen embankment between the spectators and the track, bounced, then slammed into a concrete stairwell structure and disintegrated.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The momentum of the heaviest components of the car – the engine block, radiator, and front suspension – hurtled into the crowd for almost 100 metres (330 ft), crushing all in their path.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The bonnet lid scythed through the air, "decapitating tightly jammed spectators like a guillotine".
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Spectators who had climbed onto ladders and scaffolding to get a better view of the track, and those crowding to use the underpass to get to the pits, found themselves in the way of the lethal debris.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Jaguar driver Duncan Hamilton, watching from the pit wall, recalled, "The scene on the other side of the road was indescribable.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The dead and dying were everywhere; the cries of pain, anguish, and despair screamed catastrophe.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] When the rest of Levegh's car landed on the embankment, the rear-mounted fuel tank exploded.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The fuel fire raised the temperature of the remaining Elektron bodywork past its ignition temperature, which was lower than that of other metal alloys due to its high magnesium content.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The alloy burst into white-hot flames, showering the track and crowd with magnesium embers, made worse by rescue workers unfamiliar with magnesium fires pouring water onto the inferno, greatly intensifying the flames.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] As a result, the car burned for several hours.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Meanwhile, Macklin's car, heavily damaged, rammed the left-side barrier, then veered to the right of the track into the pit lane, narrowly missing Kling's Mercedes-Benz, Roberto Mieres's Maserati, and Don Beauman's Jaguar, all of which were already in the pits refuelling before the accident.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Macklin, having got through the incident with no injuries, jumped out of his wrecked car and over the bank.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Hawthorn had overshot his pits and stopped.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Getting out, he was immediately ordered by his team to get back in and do another lap to get away from the total confusion and danger.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] When the pit stopped during the next lap, he staggered out of the car thinking that he had caused the catastrophe.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Ivor Bueb and Norman Dewis, both Le Mans debutants, had to step into their respective cars for their first driver stints.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] John Fitch, Levegh's American co-driver, had suited up and was ready to take over the car at the upcoming pit stop, and was standing with Levegh's wife, Denise Bouillin, both of them witnessing the catastrophe.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Levegh's lifeless and severely burned body lay in full view on the pavement until a *gendarme* hauled down a banner to cover it.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Half an hour after the crash, Fitch realised that news was likely being broadcast on the radio, and he needed to telephone his family to reassure them that he was not the driver of the crashed car.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] When he got to the media centre to use a telephone, he overheard a reporter filing that 48 deaths were already confirmed.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] When Fitch returned to his pit, he urged the Mercedes team to withdraw from the race, as continuing to compete would be a public relations disaster for Mercedes-Benz regardless of whether they won or lost.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Team manager Alfred Neubauer had already reached the same conclusion, but did not have the authority to make such a decision.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Despite expectations for the race to be red-flagged and stopped entirely, race officials, led by race director Charles Faroux, kept the race running.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In the days after the disaster, several explanations were offered by Faroux for this course of action.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] After an emergency meeting and vote of Mercedes-Benz company directors by telephone in Stuttgart, West Germany, Neubauer got the call approving his team's withdrawal just before midnight.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Waiting until 1:45 am, when many spectators had left, he stepped onto the track and quietly called his cars into the pits, at the time running first and third.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Their retirement was briefly announced over the public address system.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The Mercedes trucks were packed up and gone by morning.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Chief engineer Rudolf Uhlenhaut had gone to the Jaguar pits to ask if the Jaguar team would respond in kind, out of respect for the crash victims.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Jaguar team manager "Lofty" England declined.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Hawthorn and the Jaguar team kept racing.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] With the Mercedes team withdrawn and the Ferraris all out of commission, Jaguar's main competition had gone.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Hawthorn and Bueb won the race by a margin of five laps from Aston Martin.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The weather had closed in on Sunday morning, and there was no victory celebration.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] However, a press photograph showed Hawthorn smiling on the podium drinking from the victor's bottle of champagne.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The French magazine *L'Auto-Journal* published it with the sarcastic caption, "*À votre santé, Monsieur Hawthorn!*" (English: "To your health ('Cheers'), Mr.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] More than 80 spectators, plus Levegh, were killed, either by flying debris or from the fire, with a further 120 to 178 injured.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Other observers estimated the toll to be higher.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] It has remained the most fatal crash in motorsport history.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] A special Mass was held in the morning in the Le Mans Cathedral for the first funerals of the victims.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The death toll led to an immediate temporary ban on motorsports in France, Spain, Switzerland, West Germany, and other nations, until racetracks could be brought to a higher safety standard.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In the United States, the American Automobile Association (AAA) dissolved their Contest Board that had been the primary sanctioning body for motorsport in the US, including the Indianapolis 500, since 1904.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] It decided that auto racing detracted from its primary goals, and the United States Automobile Club was formed to take over the race sanctioning and officiating.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Most countries lifted their racing bans within a year after the disaster.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] France, as the host of Le Mans, lifted their complete ban on 14 September 1955.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] On that date, the Ministry of the Interior released new regulations for racing events and codified the approval process that future racing events would need to follow.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In contrast, Switzerland's ban persisted for more than 60 years.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] This forced Swiss racing promoters to organize circuit events in foreign countries including France, Italy, and West Germany.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In 2003, the Federal Assembly of Switzerland started a discussion about whether this ban should be lifted.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The discussion focused on traffic policy and environmental questions rather than on safety.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] On 10 June 2009, the *Ständerat* (upper house of the Swiss parliament) defeated a proposal to lift the ban for the second time.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In 2015, the ban was relaxed for electric vehicles only, such as cars involved in Formula E electric racing.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The ban was fully lifted in May 2022, officially taking effect in July 2026.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The next round of the World Sportscar Championship at the Nürburgring was cancelled, as was the Carrera Panamericana.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The rest of the 1955 World Sportscar Championship season was completed, with the remaining two races at the British RAC Tourist Trophy and the Italian Targa Florio, although they were not run until September and October, several months after the catastrophe.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Mercedes-Benz won both of these events, and was able to secure the constructors championship for the season.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Following the achievement, Mercedes withdrew from motorsport.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The crash caused some drivers present, including Americans Fitch (after completing the season with Mercedes), Phil Walters, and Sherwood Johnston, to retire from racing.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Macklin also decided to retire after being involved in another fatal crash, during the 1955 RAC Tourist Trophy race at Dundrod Circuit.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] At the Circuit de la Sarthe, the audience stands at the pits were demolished.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Much recrimination was directed at Hawthorn, saying that he had suddenly cut in front of Macklin and slammed on the brakes near the entrance to the pits, forcing Macklin to take evasive action into the path of Levegh.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] This became the semi-official pronouncement of the Mercedes team and Macklin's story.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The Jaguar team, in turn, questioned the fitness and competence of Macklin and Levegh as drivers.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Initial media accounts were shown to be inaccurate by subsequent analysis of photographic evidence conducted by *Road & Track* editor (and 1955 second-place finisher) Paul Frère in 1975.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Additional details emerged when the stills reviewed by Frère were converted to video form.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The media also speculated on the violent fire that engulfed the wreck, which intensified when fire marshals poured their water-based extinguishers on the flames.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] They suggested that Mercedes-Benz had tampered with the official fuel-supply with an explosive additive, but the intensity of the fire was due instead to the magnesium-alloy construction of the chassis.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Neubauer got the French authorities to test residual fuel left in the wreck's fuel injection, and the result vindicated the company.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Opinions differed amongst the other drivers as to who was directly to blame for the crash, and such differences remain to this day.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Macklin claimed that Hawthorn's move to the pits was sudden, causing an emergency that led him to swerve into Levegh's path.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Years later, Fitch claimed, based on his own recollection and from what he heard from others, that Hawthorn had caused it.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Dewis ventured the opinions that Macklin's move around Hawthorn was "careless", and that Levegh was "not competent" to meet the demands of driving at the speeds the 300SLR was capable of.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Both Jaguar and Mercedes-Benz issued official statements, mainly in self-defence against the accusations levelled against them and their drivers.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Neubauer limited himself to suggesting improvements to the pit straight and making pit-stops safer.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The action was still unresolved when Hawthorn was killed in a non-racing crash on the Guildford bypass in 1959 while overtaking a Mercedes-Benz in his Jaguar.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The official government inquiry into the accident called officials, drivers, and team personnel to be questioned and give evidence.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The wreckage was examined, tested and returned to Mercedes-Benz nearly twelve months after the catastrophe.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In the end, the enquiry ruled that no specific driver was responsible for the crash, and that it was merely a "terrible" racing incident.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The death of the spectators was blamed on inadequate safety standards for the track design.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Tony Rolt and other drivers had been raising concerns about the pit straight since 1953.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Over the next year, the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO) set about making extensive track improvements and infrastructure changes at the Circuit de la Sarthe—the pit straight was redesigned and widened to remove the kink just before the start-finish line, and to give room for a deceleration lane.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The pits complex was pulled down and rebuilt, giving more room to the teams, but thereby limiting spaces to 52 starters rather than the previous 60.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The grandstand was demolished and rebuilt with new spectator terraces and a wide ditch between them and the racetrack.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Track safety technology and practices evolved slowly until F1 driver Jackie Stewart organized a campaign to advocate for better safety measures ten years later.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Stewart's campaign gained momentum after the deaths of Lorenzo Bandini and Jim Clark.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] American John Fitch became a major safety advocate and began active development of safer road cars and racing circuits.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] He invented traffic safety devices currently in use on highways, including the sand-and-air-filled *Fitch barrels*.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Macklin's Austin-Healey 100 was sold to several private buyers before appearing on the public auction block.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] In December 2011, the car, estimated to raise £800,000 before the auction, was sold for £843,000.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] The car retained the original engine SPL 261-BN, but was reported to be in 'barn find' condition.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] It was then restored to its original condition.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Mercedes-Benz withdrew from motorsports until 1985, although the withdrawal had already been decided before the race and had not been caused by the accident.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] After returning to sports car racing in the mid-1980s, initially as an engine supplier, Mercedes went on to win the 1989 Le Mans race in partnership with Sauber Motorsport.
[src:switzerland/1955-le-mans-disaster] Mercedes went on to compete in the championship during the 1990s as a works team before withdrawing for a second and final time in 1999, following a series of spectacular but non-fatal crashes of the Mercedes-Benz CLR.
[src:switzerland/41] The Swiss telephone numbering plan implements the ITU-T recommendation E.164 and is designated E.164/2002, based on its last major revision in 2002.
[src:switzerland/41] It is a closed numbering plan, which means that all telephone numbers, including the area code, have a fixed number of digits.
[src:switzerland/41] Swiss area codes are officially termed *national destination codes* (NDC).
[src:switzerland/41] A complete telephone number consists of ten digits: *0xx xxx xx xx*.
[src:switzerland/41] Two formats are distinguished: three digits for the NDC and seven digits for the subscriber number, and four digits for the NDC and six digits for the subscriber number.
[src:switzerland/41] The associated dial plan requires that all numbers, even for local calls, must be dialed with the assigned NDC, in contrast to previous plans.
[src:switzerland/41] When dialing from within the country, a prefix *0* must be dialed.
[src:switzerland/41] The plan was amended a few times, e.g., the transition of numbering zone 01 into 044 and 043.
[src:switzerland/41] The national destination code (NDC) is the area code for Swiss telephone numbers.
[src:switzerland/41] Within Switzerland the trunk code 0 must be dialed before the NDC, while it is not needed from international locations.
[src:switzerland/41] Telephone numbers are portable between numbering zones (ZN) or between mobile operators, and therefore an NDC does not imply that a caller is actually located in a particular zone or is serviced by any particular mobile operator.
[src:switzerland/41] For landlines it is now merely an indication of the region where the number was originally attributed to a subscriber.
[src:switzerland/41] The national destination codes are the following.
[src:switzerland/41] Short dialing codes are assigned for special services or network features.
[src:switzerland/41] Instead of E.164/2002, another more ambitious numbering plan was proposed.
[src:switzerland/41] In this plan the prefix 0 was discarded, and the area codes were defined differently, with 20 to 49 for geographic areas, 50 to 59 reserved, 60-69 for nationwide numbering, 70-79 for mobile services, 80-89 for shared-cost and toll-free numbers, and 90 for premium-rate services.
[src:switzerland/41] The plan was not implemented because it required too many phone number and prefix changes, with associated high costs.
[src:switzerland/41] On 29 March 2002 the Swiss dialing plan changed to a closed dialing plan, i.e. the zone prefix become mandatory also for local calls.
[src:switzerland/41] The previous plan removed a lot of area prefixes and added the seventh digit in phone numbers (usually a phone number (0cc) yx xx xx became (0dd) zzx xx xx).
[src:switzerland/41] The German municipality of Büsingen am Hochrhein, an enclave within the canton of Schaffhausen, uses the Swiss telecom network, with numbers having the prefix 052, alongside that of Germany, from which numbers must be dialled in the international format as 004152.
[src:switzerland/41] The Italian municipality of Campione d'Italia, an exclave within the Swiss canton of Ticino, uses the Swiss telephone network and is part of the Swiss numbering plan, although some Italian numbers are in use by the municipal council, which use the same +39 031 numbering range as the town of Como.
[src:switzerland/41] Liechtenstein previously used the Swiss telephone numbering plan with the area code 075.
[src:switzerland/41] (This was dialled as +41 75 from outside Switzerland and Liechtenstein).
[src:switzerland/41] However, on 5 April 1999, it adopted its own international code +423.
[src:switzerland/41] Consequently, calls from Switzerland now require international dialling, using the **00423** prefix and the seven-digit number.
[src:switzerland/ch] The domain *ch*, as with other ccTLDs, is based on the ISO 3166-2 code for Switzerland derived from *Confoederatio Helvetica* (Helvetic Confederation), the Latin name for the country, which was used because of its neutrality with regard to the four official languages of Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/ch] Made available in 1987, only two years after .com, it is administered by SWITCH Information Technology Services.
[src:switzerland/ch] Second-level domain names must be at least three letters long.
[src:switzerland/ch] Two-letter subdomain names are restricted to the Swiss cantons, as well as the domain ch.ch of the Federal Chancellery of Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/ch] The only exception has been the former domain of the Expo.02 which was held in Switzerland, www.expo.02.ch.
[src:switzerland/ch] Registrations of internationalized domain names have been accepted since March 2004.
[src:switzerland/ch] .ch has been of a rising interest to Chinese domain investors for several reasons.
[src:switzerland/ch] According to EuropeID.com, the domain .ch still has many valuable English keywords and short letter and number combinations left.
[src:switzerland/ch] A contributing factor may be because the majority of .ch registrations are in German, leaving many English words available.
[src:switzerland/ch] In addition, with two million domains under .ch being registered, most of the reserved domains have the European market in mind, allowing valuable domains for other languages such as Chinese keywords in the Latin script being registered at a normal price.
[src:switzerland/ch] The .ch domain is very popular in domain hacks, used to spell words and names that end in "ch".
[src:switzerland/ch] For example, Techcrunch's tcrn.ch, as well as the University of Michigan's myumi.ch and umresear.ch.
[src:switzerland/ch] This phenomenon is not limited to English; to take another example, the domain scha.ch (*Schach,* German for "chess") has been registered.
[src:switzerland/ch] The Federal Office of Communications (OFCOM) has begun registering .swiss domains as of 7 September 2015 meant to augment the traditional .ch TLD.
[src:switzerland/ch] Applicants must currently have a "registered place of business and a physical administrative base in Switzerland" to apply.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland is a federal republic composed of 26 cantons, with Bern serving as the federal city and the seat of the national government.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The country encompasses four principal linguistic and cultural regions—German, French, Italian, and Romansh—reflecting a long-standing tradition of multilingualism and cultural pluralism.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Swiss national identity nonetheless remains fairly cohesive, rooted in a shared historical background, common values such as federalism and direct democracy, and Alpine symbolism.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Swiss nationhood transcends language, ethnicity, and religion, leading to Switzerland being described as a *Willensnation* ("nation of volition") rather than a conventional nation state.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The country originates from the Old Swiss Confederacy established in the Late Middle Ages as a defensive and commercial alliance; the Federal Charter of 1291 is considered the country's founding document.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The confederation steadily expanded and consolidated despite external threats and internal political and religious strife.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Swiss independence from the Holy Roman Empire was formally recognized in the Peace of Westphalia in 1648.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The confederation was among the first and few republics of the early modern period, and the only one besides San Marino to survive the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland remained a network of self-governing states until 1798, when revolutionary France invaded and imposed the centralist Helvetic Republic.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Napoleon abolished the republic in 1803 and reinstated a confederation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland has maintained a policy of armed neutrality since the 16th century and has not fought an international war since 1815.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It joined the Council of Europe in 1964 and the United Nations (UN) in 2002, pursuing an active foreign policy that includes frequent involvement in peace building and global governance.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland is the birthplace of the Red Cross and hosts the headquarters or offices of most major international institutions, including the WTO, the WHO, the ILO, FIFA, the WEF, and the UN.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It is a founding member of the European Free Trade Association (EFTA) and participates in the European single market and the Schengen Area.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland is among the world's most developed countries, with the highest nominal wealth per adult and the eighth-highest gross domestic product (GDP) per capita.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It performs highly on several international metrics, including economic competitiveness, democratic governance, and press freedom.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Zurich, Geneva and Basel rank among the highest in quality of life, albeit with some of the highest costs of living.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland has a longstanding banking and financial sector, advanced pharmaceutical and biotechnology industries, and a strong tradition of watchmaking, precision engineering, and technology.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It is known for its chocolate and cheese production, well-developed tourism industry, and growing startup sector.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The English name *Switzerland* compounds *Switzer*, an obsolete term for a Swiss person which was in use during the 16th to 19th centuries, with the common English suffix -land denoting a region or country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The English adjective *Swiss* is a loanword from French **Suisse**, also in use since the 16th century.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The name *Switzer* is from the Alemannic **Schwiizer**, in origin an inhabitant of *Schwyz* and its associated territory, one of the *Waldstätte* cantons which formed the nucleus of the Old Swiss Confederacy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss began to adopt the name for themselves after the Swabian War of 1499, used alongside the term for "Confederates", *Eidgenossen* (literally: *comrades by oath*), used since the 14th century.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The ISO 3166-1 data codes for Switzerland, CH and CHE, are derived from Latin *Confoederatio Helvetica* (*Helvetic Confederation*).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The toponym *Schwyz* itself was first attested in 972, as Old High German **Suittes**, perhaps related to **swedan** 'to burn' (cf.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Old Norse *svíða* 'to singe, burn'), referring to the area of forest that was burned and cleared to build.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The name was extended to the area dominated by the canton, and after the Swabian War of 1499 gradually came to be used for the entire Confederation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss German name of the country, **Schwiiz**, is homophonous to that of the canton and the settlement, but distinguished by the use of the definite article (**d'Schwiiz** for the Confederation, but simply **Schwyz** for the canton and the town).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The long [iː] of Swiss German is historically and still often today spelled ⟨y⟩ rather than ⟨ii⟩, preserving the original identity of the two names even in writing.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Latin name *Confoederatio Helvetica* was neologised and introduced gradually after the formation of the federal state in 1848, harking back to the Napoleonic Helvetic Republic.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It appeared on coins from 1879, inscribed on the Federal Palace in 1902 and after 1948 used in the official seal (e.g., the ISO banking code "CHF" for the Swiss franc, the Swiss postage stamps ('HELVETIA') and the country top-level domain ".ch", are both taken from the state's Latin name).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The name *Helvetica* is derived from the *Helvetii*, a Gaulish tribe living on the Swiss Plateau before the Roman era.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It in turn, gives its name to a typeface developed in 1960.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The state of Switzerland took its present form with the adoption of the Swiss Federal Constitution in 1848.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland's precursors established a defensive alliance in 1291, forming a loose confederation that persisted for centuries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The oldest traces of hominid existence in Switzerland date to about 150,000 years ago.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The oldest known farming settlements in Switzerland, which were found at Gächlingen, date to around 5300 BC.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The earliest known tribes formed the Hallstatt and La Tène cultures, named after the archaeological site of La Tène on the north side of Lake Neuchâtel.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] La Tène culture developed and flourished during the late Iron Age from around 450 BC, possibly influenced by Greek and Etruscan civilisations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] One of the most prominent La Tène tribes were the Helvetii, who primarily occupied the Swiss Plateau, alongside the Rhaetians in the eastern regions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Facing pressures from Germanic tribes, in 58 BC, the Helvetii, influenced by Orgetorix, a wealthy aristocrat, decided to abandon the Swiss Plateau for better opportunities in western Gallia.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] After Orgetorix's mysterious death, the tribe continued their migration but was decisively defeated by Julius Caesar's armies at the Battle of Bibracte, in present-day eastern France.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Following their defeat, the Helvetii were forced by Caesar to return to their original lands, where they were subjected to stringent restrictions on their autonomy and movements.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 15 BC, Tiberius (later the second Roman emperor) and his brother Drusus conquered the Alps, integrating them into the Roman Empire.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The area occupied by the Helvetii first became part of Rome's Gallia Belgica province and then of its Germania Superior province.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The eastern portion of modern Switzerland was integrated into the Roman province of Raetia.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Sometime around the start of the Common Era, the Romans maintained a large camp called Vindonissa, now a ruin at the confluence of the Aare and Reuss rivers, near the town of Windisch.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The first and second century AD was an age of prosperity on the Swiss Plateau.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Towns such as Aventicum, Iulia Equestris and Augusta Raurica reached a remarkable size, while hundreds of agricultural estates (Villae rusticae) were established in the countryside.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Around 260 AD, the fall of the Agri Decumates territory north of the Rhine transformed today's Switzerland into a frontier land of the Empire.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Repeated raids by the Alamanni tribes provoked the ruin of the Roman towns and economy, forcing the population to shelter near Roman fortresses, like the Castrum Rauracense near Augusta Raurica.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Empire built another line of defence at the north border (the so-called Donau-Iller-Rhine-Limes).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] At the end of the fourth century, the increased Germanic pressure forced the Romans to abandon the linear defence concept.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss Plateau was finally open to Germanic tribes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In the Early Middle Ages, from the end of the fourth century, the western extent of modern-day Switzerland was part of the territory of the Kings of the Burgundians, who introduced the French language to the area.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Alemanni settled the Swiss Plateau in the fifth century and the valleys of the Alps in the eighth century, forming Alemannia.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Modern-day Switzerland was then divided between the kingdoms of Alemannia and Burgundy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The entire region became part of the expanding Frankish Empire in the sixth century, following Clovis I's victory over the Alemanni at Tolbiac in 504 AD, and later Frankish domination of the Burgundians.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Throughout the rest of the sixth, seventh and eighth centuries, Swiss regions continued under Frankish hegemony (Merovingian and Carolingian dynasties) but after its extension under Charlemagne, the Frankish Empire was divided by the Treaty of Verdun in 843.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The territories of present-day Switzerland became divided into Middle Francia and East Francia until they were reunified under the Holy Roman Empire around 1000 AD.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In the 10th century, as the rule of the Carolingians waned, Magyars destroyed Basel in 917 and St.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In response, Henry the Fowler, the then ruler of East Francia, decreed the fortification of key settlements to defend against these invasions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Large villages and towns, including strategic locations like Zurich and St.Gallen, were fortified.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This initiative led to the development of what were essentially early urban strongholds and city governments in Eastern Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] By 1200, the Swiss Plateau comprised the dominions of the houses of Savoy, Zähringer, Habsburg, and Kyburg.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Some regions (Uri, Schwyz, Unterwalden, later known as *Waldstätten*) were accorded the Imperial immediacy to grant the empire direct control over the mountain passes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] With the extinction of its male line in 1263, the Kyburg dynasty fell in AD 1264.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Habsburgs under King Rudolph I (Holy Roman Emperor in 1273) laid claim to the Kyburg lands and annexed them, extending their territory to the eastern Swiss Plateau.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Old Swiss Confederacy was an alliance among the valley communities of the central Alps.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Confederacy was governed by nobles and patricians of various cantons who facilitated management of common interests and ensured peace on mountain trade routes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Federal Charter of 1291 is considered the confederacy's founding document, even though similar alliances likely existed decades earlier.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The document was agreed among the rural communes of Uri, Schwyz, and Unterwalden.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] By 1353, the three original cantons had joined with the cantons of Glarus and Zug and the Lucerne, Zurich and Bern city-states to form the "Old Confederacy" of eight states that obtained through the end of the 15th century.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The expansion led to increased power and wealth for the confederation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] By 1460, the confederates controlled most of the territory south and west of the Rhine to the Alps and the Jura Mountains, and the University of Basel was founded (with a faculty of medicine) establishing a tradition of chemical and medical research.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This increased after victories against the Habsburgs (Battle of Sempach, Battle of Näfels), over Charles the Bold of Burgundy during the 1470s, and the success of the Swiss mercenaries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss victory in the Swabian War against the Swabian League of Emperor Maximilian I in 1499 amounted to *de facto* independence within the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1501, Basel and Schaffhausen joined the Old Swiss Confederacy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Confederacy acquired a reputation of invincibility during these earlier wars, but expansion of the confederation suffered a setback in 1515 with the Swiss defeat in the Battle of Marignano.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This ended the so-called "heroic" epoch of Swiss history.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The success of Zwingli's Reformation in some cantons led to inter-cantonal religious conflicts in 1529 and 1531 (Wars of Kappel).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It was not until more than one hundred years after these internal wars that, in 1648, under the Peace of Westphalia, European countries recognised Switzerland's independence from the Holy Roman Empire and its neutrality.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] During the Early Modern period of Swiss history, the growing authoritarianism of the patriciate families combined with a financial crisis in the wake of the Thirty Years' War led to the Swiss peasant war of 1653.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In the background to this struggle, the conflict between Catholic and Protestant cantons persisted, erupting in further violence at the First War of Villmergen, in 1656, and the Toggenburg War (or Second War of Villmergen), in 1712.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1798, the revolutionary French government invaded Switzerland and imposed a new unified constitution.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This centralised the government of the country, effectively abolishing the cantons: moreover, Mülhausen left Switzerland and the Valtellina valley became part of the Cisalpine Republic.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The new regime, known as the Helvetic Republic, was highly unpopular.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] An invading foreign army had imposed and destroyed centuries of tradition, making Switzerland nothing more than a French satellite state.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The fierce French suppression of the Nidwalden Revolt in September 1798 was an example of the oppressive presence of the French Army and the local population's resistance to the occupation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] When war broke out between France and its rivals, Russian and Austrian forces invaded Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss refused to fight alongside the French in the name of the Helvetic Republic.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1803 Napoleon organised a meeting of the leading Swiss politicians from both sides in Paris.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Act of Mediation was the result, which largely restored Swiss autonomy and introduced a Confederation of 19 cantons.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Henceforth, much of Swiss politics would concern balancing the cantons' tradition of self-rule with the need for a central government.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1815, the Congress of Vienna fully re-established Swiss independence, and the European powers recognised permanent Swiss neutrality.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Swiss troops served foreign governments until 1860 when they fought in the siege of Gaeta.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The treaty allowed Switzerland to increase its territory, with the admission of the cantons of Valais, Neuchâtel and Geneva.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland's borders saw only minor adjustments thereafter.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The restoration of power to the patriciate was only temporary.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] After a period of unrest with repeated violent clashes, such as the Züriputsch of 1839, civil war (the *Sonderbundskrieg*) broke out in 1847, when some Catholic cantons tried to set up a separate alliance (the *Sonderbund*).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The war lasted less than a month, causing fewer than 100 casualties, most of which were through friendly fire.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The *Sonderbundskrieg* had a significant impact on the psychology and society of Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The war convinced most Swiss of the need for unity and strength.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Swiss from all strata of society, whether Catholic or Protestant, from the liberal or conservative current, realised that the cantons would profit more from merging their economic and religious interests.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Thus, while the rest of Europe saw revolutionary uprisings, the Swiss created a constitution that provided for a federal layout, much of it inspired by the United States Constitution.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This new constitution provided central authority while leaving the cantons the right to self-government on local issues.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Giving credit to those who favoured the power of the cantons (the Sonderbund Kantone), the national assembly was divided between an upper house (the Council of States, two representatives per canton) and a lower house (the National Council, with representatives elected from across the country).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Referendums were made mandatory for any amendments.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This new constitution ended the legal power of nobility in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] A single system of weights and measures was introduced, and in 1850, the Swiss franc became the Swiss single currency, complemented by the WIR franc in 1934.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Article 11 of the constitution forbade sending troops to serve abroad, marking the end of foreign service.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It came with the exception of serving the Holy See, and the Swiss were still obliged to serve Francis II of the Two Sicilies, with Swiss Guards present at the siege of Gaeta in 1860.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] An important clause of the constitution was that it could be entirely rewritten, if necessary, thus enabling it to evolve as a whole rather than being modified one amendment at a time.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This need soon proved itself when the rise in population and the Industrial Revolution that followed led to calls to modify the constitution accordingly.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The population rejected an early draft in 1872, but modifications led to its acceptance in 1874.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It introduced the facultative referendum for laws at the federal level.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It also established federal responsibility for defence, trade, and legal matters.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1891, the constitution was revised with uncommonly strong elements of direct democracy, which remain unique today.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland was not invaded during either of the world wars.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] During World War I, Switzerland was home to the revolutionary and founder of the Soviet Union Vladimir Illych Ulyanov (Vladimir Lenin) who remained there until 1917.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Swiss neutrality was seriously questioned by the short-lived Grimm–Hoffmann affair in 1917.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1920, Switzerland joined the League of Nations, which was based in Geneva, after it was exempted from military requirements.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] During World War II, detailed invasion plans were drawn up by the Germans, but Switzerland was never attacked.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland was able to remain independent through a combination of military deterrence, concessions to Germany, and good fortune, as larger events during the war intervened.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] General Henri Guisan, appointed the commander-in-chief for the duration of the war, ordered a general mobilisation of the armed forces.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss military strategy changed from static defence at the borders to organised long-term attrition and withdrawal to strong, well-stockpiled positions high in the Alps, known as the Reduit.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland was an important base for espionage by both sides and often mediated communications between the Axis and Allied powers.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland's trade was blockaded by both the Allies and the Axis.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Economic cooperation with Nazi Germany; such as purchasing gold (enabling Germany to purchase foreign goods) and extension of credit varied according to the perceived likelihood of invasion and the availability of other trading partners.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Concessions reached a peak after a crucial rail link through Vichy France was severed in 1942, leaving Switzerland (together with Liechtenstein) entirely isolated from the wider world by Axis-controlled territory.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Over the course of the war, Switzerland interned over 300,000 refugees aided by the International Red Cross, based in Geneva.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Strict immigration and asylum policies and the financial relationships with Nazi Germany became controversial by the end of the 20th century.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] During the war, the Swiss Air Force engaged aircraft of both sides, shooting down 11 intruding Luftwaffe planes in May and June 1940, then forcing down other intruders after a change of policy following threats from Germany.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Over 100 Allied bombers and their crews were interned.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Between 1940 and 1945, Switzerland was bombed by the Allies, causing fatalities and property damage.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Among the cities and towns bombed were Basel, Brusio, Chiasso, Cornol, Geneva, Koblenz, Niederweningen, Rafz, Renens, Samedan, Schaffhausen, Stein am Rhein, Tägerwilen, Thayngen, Vals, and Zurich.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Allied forces maintained that the bombings, which violated the 96th Article of War, resulted from navigation errors, equipment failure, weather conditions, and pilot errors.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss expressed fear and concern that the bombings were intended to put pressure on Switzerland to end economic cooperation and neutrality with Nazi Germany.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Court-martial proceedings took place in England.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland's attitude towards refugees was complicated and controversial; over the course of the war, it admitted as many as 300,000 refugees while refusing tens of thousands more, including Jews persecuted by the Nazis.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] After the war, the Swiss government exported credits through the charitable fund known as the *Schweizerspende* and donated to the Marshall Plan to help Europe's recovery, efforts that ultimately benefited the Swiss economy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] During the Cold War, Swiss authorities considered the construction of a Swiss nuclear bomb.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Leading nuclear physicists at the Federal Institute of Technology Zurich such as Paul Scherrer made this a realistic possibility.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1988, the Paul Scherrer Institute was founded in his name to explore the therapeutic uses of neutron scattering technologies.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Financial problems with the defence budget and ethical considerations prevented the substantial funds from being allocated, and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty of 1968 was seen as a valid alternative.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Plans for building nuclear weapons were dropped by 1988.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland joined the Council of Europe in 1963.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland was the last Western republic (the Principality of Liechtenstein followed in 1984) to grant women the right to vote.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Some Swiss cantons approved this in 1959, while at the federal level, it was achieved in 1971 and, after resistance, in the last canton Appenzell Innerrhoden (one of only two remaining *Landsgemeinde*, along with Glarus) in 1990.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] After obtaining suffrage at the federal level, women quickly rose in political significance.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The first woman on the seven-member Federal Council executive was Elisabeth Kopp, who served from 1984 to 1989, and the first female president was Ruth Dreifuss in 1999.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 1979 areas from the canton of Bern attained independence from the Bernese, forming the new canton of Jura.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] On 18 April 1999, the Swiss population and the cantons voted in favour of a completely revised federal constitution.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 2002 Switzerland became a full member of the United Nations, leaving Vatican City as the last widely recognised state without full UN membership.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland is a founding member of the EFTA but not the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] An application for membership in the European Union was sent in May 1992, but did not advance since rejecting the EEA in December 1992 when Switzerland conducted a referendum on the EEA.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Several referendums on the EU issue ensued; due to opposition from the citizens, the membership application was withdrawn.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Nonetheless, Swiss law is gradually changing to conform with that of the EU, and the government signed bilateral agreements with the European Union.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland, together with Liechtenstein, has been surrounded by the EU since Austria's entry in 1995.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] On 5 June 2005, Swiss voters agreed by a 55% majority to join the Schengen treaty, a result that EU commentators regarded as a sign of support.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In September 2020, a referendum calling for a vote to end the pact that allowed a free movement of people from the EU was introduced by the Swiss People's Party (SVP).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] However, voters rejected the attempt to retake control of immigration, defeating the motion by a roughly 63%–37% margin.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] On 9 February 2014, 50.3% of Swiss voters approved a ballot initiative launched by the Swiss People's Party (SVP/UDC) to restrict immigration.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This initiative was mostly backed by rural (57.6% approval) and suburban groups (51.2% approval), and isolated towns (51.3% approval) as well as by a strong majority (69.2% approval) in Ticino, while metropolitan centres (58.5% rejection) and the French-speaking part (58.5% rejection) rejected it.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In December 2016, a political compromise with the EU was attained that eliminated quotas on EU citizens, but still allowed favourable treatment of Swiss-based job applicants.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] On 27 September 2020, 62% of Swiss voters rejected the anti-free movement referendum by SVP.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Extending across the north and south side of the Alps in west-central Europe, Switzerland encompasses diverse landscapes and climates across its 41,291 square kilometres (15,943 sq mi).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland lies between latitudes 45° and 48° N, and longitudes 5° and 11° E.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It contains three basic topographical areas: the Swiss Alps to the south, the Swiss Plateau or Central Plateau, and the Jura Mountains on the west.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Alps are a mountain range running across the central and south of the country, constituting about 60% of the country's area.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The majority of the population live on the Swiss Plateau.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss Alps host many glaciers, covering 1,063 square kilometres (410 mi2).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] From these originate the headwaters of several major rivers, such as the Rhine, Inn, Ticino and Rhône, which flow in the four cardinal directions, spreading across Europe.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The hydrographic network includes several of the largest bodies of fresh water in Central and Western Europe, among which are Lake Geneva (Lac Léman in French), Lake Constance (Bodensee in German) and Lake Maggiore.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland has more than 1500 lakes and contains 6% of Europe's freshwater stock.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Lakes and glaciers cover about 6% of the national territory.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Lake Geneva is the largest lake and is shared with France.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Rhône is both the main source and outflow of Lake Geneva.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Lake Constance is the second largest and, like Lake Geneva, an intermediate step by the Rhine at the border with Austria and Germany.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] While the Rhône flows into the Mediterranean Sea at the French Camargue region and the Rhine flows into the North Sea at Rotterdam, about 1,000 kilometres (620 miles) apart, both springs are only about 22 kilometres (14 miles) apart in the Swiss Alps.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] 90% of Switzerland's 65,000-kilometre-long network of rivers and streams have been straightened, dammed, canalized or channelled underground, in an effort to prevent natural disasters such as flooding, landslides, and avalanches.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] 80% of all Swiss drinking water comes from groundwater sources.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Forty-eight mountains are 4,000 metres (13,000 ft) or higher in height.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] At 4,634 m (15,203 ft), Monte Rosa is the highest, although the Matterhorn (4,478 m or 14,692 ft) is the best known.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Both are located within the Pennine Alps in the canton of Valais, on the border with Italy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The section of the Bernese Alps above the deep glacial Lauterbrunnen valley, containing 72 waterfalls, is well known for the Jungfrau (4,158 m or 13,642 ft) Eiger and Mönch peaks, and its many picturesque valleys.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In the southeast the long Engadin Valley, encompassing St.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Moritz, is also well known; the highest peak in the neighbouring Bernina Alps is Piz Bernina (4,049 m or 13,284 ft).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss Plateau has greater open and hilly landscapes, partly forested, partly open pastures, usually with grazing herds or vegetable and fruit fields, but it is still hilly.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Large lakes and the biggest Swiss cities are found there.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland contains two small enclaves: Büsingen belongs to Germany, while Campione d'Italia belongs to Italy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The Swiss climate is generally temperate, but can vary greatly across localities, from glacial conditions on the mountaintops to the near-Mediterranean climate at Switzerland's southern tip.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Some valley areas in the southern part of Switzerland offer cold-hardy palm trees, for example, the dwarf palm or the Chinese hemp palm.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Summers tend to be warm and humid at times with periodic rainfall, ideal for pastures/grazing.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The less humid winters in the mountains may see weeks-long intervals of stable conditions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] At the same time, the lower lands tend to suffer from inversion during such periods, hiding the sun.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] A weather phenomenon known as the föhn (with an identical effect to the chinook wind) can occur any time and is characterised by an unexpectedly warm wind, bringing low relative humidity air to the north of the Alps during rainfall periods south of the main Alpine ridge.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] This works both ways across the alps but is more efficient if blowing from the south due to the steeper step for oncoming wind.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Valleys running south to north trigger the strongest effect.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The driest conditions persist in all inner alpine valleys that receive less rain because arriving clouds lose a lot of their moisture content while crossing the mountains before reaching these areas.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Large alpine areas such as Graubünden remain drier than pre-alpine areas, and as in the main valley of the Valais, wine grapes are grown there.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The wettest conditions persist in the high Alps and in the Ticino canton, which has much sun yet heavy bursts of rain from time to time.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Precipitation tends to be spread moderately throughout the year, with a peak in summer.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Autumn is the driest season, winter receives less precipitation than summer, yet the weather patterns in Switzerland are not in a stable climate system.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] They can vary from year to year with no strict and predictable periods.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Global warming has changed the climate in Switzerland, and extreme weather events, including heat waves and heavy rainfall, have become more frequent.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Since the pre-industrial period of 1871–1900, the national average temperature has risen by 2.9 °C, more than twice the global average.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Since 1971, warming has increased continuously every decade.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The nationwide average annual temperature in 2022 reached 7.4 °C (1.6 °C above the 1991–2020 norm), the highest value since measurements began in 1864.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The nine warmest years in Switzerland were all recorded after 2010, with 2022 being the hottest year, followed by 2023, 2024, 2018 and 2020.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland contains two terrestrial ecoregions: Western European broadleaf forests and Alps conifer and mixed forests.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland's many small valleys separated by high mountains often host unique ecologies.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The mountainous regions themselves offer a rich range of plants not found at other altitudes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The climatic, geological and topographical conditions of the alpine region make for a fragile ecosystem that is particularly sensitive to climate change.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 2020 it was ranked third out of 180 countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The country pledged to cut GHG emissions by 50% by 2030 compared to the level of 1990 and plans to reach zero emissions by 2050.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] However, access to biocapacity in Switzerland is far lower than the world average.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In 2016, Switzerland had 1.0 hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, 40 per cent less than world average of 1.6.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In contrast, in 2016, Swiss consumption required 4.6 hectares of biocapacity – their ecological footprint, 4.6 times as much as Swiss territory can support.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The remainder comes from other countries and the shared resources (such as the atmosphere impacted by greenhouse gas emissions).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 3.53/10, ranking it 150th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland ranked 9th in the Environmental Performance Index for 2024.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] It scored well in parameters including air pollution, sanitation and drinking water, waste management, and climate change mitigation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] About 85% of the population live in urban areas.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland went from a largely rural country to an urban one from 1930 to 2000.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] After 1935 urban development claimed as much of the Swiss landscape as it did during the prior 2,000 years.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Urban sprawl affects the plateau, the Jura and the Alpine foothills, raising concerns about land use.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] During the 21st century, population growth in urban areas is higher than in the countryside.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] Switzerland has a dense network of complementary large, medium and small towns.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The plateau is densely populated with about 400 people per km2 and the landscape shows uninterrupted signs of human presence.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The weight of the largest metropolitan areas – Zurich, Geneva–Lausanne, Basel and Bern – tend to increase.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The importance of these urban areas is greater than their population suggests.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] These urban centres are recognised for their high quality of life.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] The average population density in 2019 was 215.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (557/sq mi).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In the largest canton by area, Graubünden, lying entirely in the Alps, population density falls to 28.0 inhabitants per square kilometre (73/sq mi).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p01] In the canton of Zurich, with its large urban capital, the density is 926.8 per square kilometre (2,400/sq mi).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Switzerland performs in the high range on overall democratic measures, with particular weaknesses in electoral participation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Federal Constitution adopted in 1848 is the legal foundation of Switzerland's federal state.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is regularly modified by referendum and has been completely revised twice, in 1874 and 1999.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The constitution outlines rights of individuals and citizen participation in public affairs, divides the powers between the confederation and the cantons and defines federal jurisdiction and authority.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Three main bodies govern on the federal level: the Federal Assembly (legislative), the Federal Council (executive) and the federal courts (judicial).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Federal Assembly is the parliament of Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It consists of two houses: The Council of States has 46 members, two from each canton and one from each half-canton.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The National Council has 200 members, apportioned to reflect the population of each canton, and elected by proportional representation within each canton.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Members of both houses serve for four years and work part-time (*Milizsystem*).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] When both houses are in joint session, they are known collectively as the Federal Assembly.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Through optional referendums, citizens may challenge any law passed by parliament.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Federal Council is the Swiss executive.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It leads the federal administration and serves as a collective head of state.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is a collegial body of seven members, elected to four-year terms by the Federal Assembly, which oversees the council.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Each member leads a department of the federal government.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Each year, one member of the Council is elected President of the Confederation by the Assembly, with the presidency traditionally rotating between members.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The President chairs and represents the government, but has no additional powers and remains the head of their department.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The government has been a coalition of the four major political parties since 1959, each party having a number of seats that roughly reflects its share of the electorate and representation in the federal parliament.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] This distribution is called the "magic formula".
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The function of the Federal Supreme Court is to hear appeals against rulings of cantonal or federal courts.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The judges are elected by the Federal Assembly for six-year terms.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Direct democracy and federalism are hallmarks of the Swiss political system defined in the Swiss constitution.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss people are subject to three legal jurisdictions: the municipal, cantonal and federal levels.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] At the federal level, popular rights include the right to submit a federal initiative and a referendum, both of which may overturn parliamentary decisions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Federal Council and the Federal Assembly can supplement a popular initiative with a counterproposal.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Voters must then indicate their preference if both proposals are accepted.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss Confederation consists of 26 cantons.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The cantons are federated states, with permanent constitutional status and a high degree of independence relative to the subnational divisions of most countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Each canton has its own constitution and its own parliament, government, police and courts.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] However, considerable differences define the individual cantons, particularly in terms of population and geographical area.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Their populations vary between 16,003 (Appenzell Innerrhoden) and 1,487,969 (Zurich), and their area between 37 km2 (14 sq mi) (Basel-Stadt) and 7,105 km2 (2,743 sq mi) (Grisons).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] As of 2026 the cantons comprised 2,110 municipalities.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Until 1848, the loosely coupled Confederation did not have a central political organisation.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Issues thought to affect the whole Confederation were the subject of periodic meetings in various locations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 1848, the federal constitution provided that details concerning federal institutions, such as their locations, should be addressed by the Federal Assembly (BV 1848 Art.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Other federal institutions were subsequently attributed to Lausanne (Federal Supreme Court in 1872, and EPFL in 1969), Bellinzona (Federal Criminal Court, 2004), and St.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Gallen (Federal Administrative Court and Federal Patent Court, 2012).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The 1999 Constitution does not mention a Federal City, and the Federal Council has yet to address the matter.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Thus no city in Switzerland has the *official* status either of capital or of Federal City.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Nevertheless, Bern is commonly referred to as "Federal City" (German: *Bundesstadt*, French: *ville fédérale*, Italian: *città federale*).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] However the largest city, Zurich, is used when selecting a time zone on computer systems.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Traditionally, Switzerland avoids alliances that might entail military, political, or direct economic action and has been neutral since the end of its expansion in 1515.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Its policy of neutrality was internationally recognised at the Congress of Vienna in 1815.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Swiss neutrality has been questioned at times.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2002 Switzerland became a full member of the United Nations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It was the first state to join it by referendum.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland maintains diplomatic relations with almost all countries and historically has served as an intermediary between other states.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland is not a member of the European Union; the Swiss people have consistently rejected membership since the early 1990s.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] However, Switzerland does participate in the Schengen Area.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Many international institutions have headquarters in Switzerland, in part because of its policy of neutrality.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Geneva is the birthplace of the Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement, the Geneva Conventions and, since 2006, hosts the United Nations Human Rights Council.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Even though Switzerland is one of the most recent countries to join the United Nations, the Palace of Nations in Geneva is the second biggest centre for the United Nations after the headquarters in New York.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland was a founding member and hosted the League of Nations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The annual meetings of the World Economic Forum in Davos bring together business and political leaders from Switzerland and foreign countries to discuss important issues.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The headquarters of the Bank for International Settlements (BIS) moved to Basel in 1930.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland became a member of the United Nations Security Council for the 2023–2024 period.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Switzerland is the 6th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Although not a member, Switzerland maintains relationships with the EU and European countries through bilateral agreements.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss have brought their economic practices largely into conformity with those of the EU, in an effort to compete internationally.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] EU membership faces considerable negative popular sentiment.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is opposed by the conservative SVP party, the largest party in the National Council, and not advocated by several other political parties.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The membership application was formally withdrawn in 2016.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The western French-speaking areas and the urban regions of the rest of the country tend to be more pro-EU, but do not form a significant share of the population.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] An Integration Office operates under the Department of Foreign Affairs and the Department of Economic Affairs.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Seven bilateral agreements liberalised trade ties, taking effect in 2001.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] This first series of bilateral agreements included the free movement of persons.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] A second series of agreements covering nine areas was signed in 2004, including the Schengen Treaty and the Dublin Convention.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2006, a referendum approved 1 billion francs of supportive investment in Southern and Central European countries in support of positive ties to the EU as a whole.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] A further referendum will be needed to approve 300 million francs to support Romania and Bulgaria and their recent admission.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss have faced EU and international pressure to reduce banking secrecy and raise tax rates to parity with the EU.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Preparatory discussions involved four areas: the electricity market, participation in project Galileo, cooperating with the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control and certificates of origin for food products.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland is a member of the Schengen passport-free zone.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Land border checkpoints monitor goods movements, but not people.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss Armed Forces, including the Land Forces and the Air Force, are composed mostly of conscripts, male citizens aged from 20 to 34 (in exceptional cases up to 50) years.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Being a landlocked country, Switzerland has no navy; however, on lakes bordering neighbouring countries, armed boats patrol.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Swiss citizens are prohibited from serving in foreign armies, except for the Swiss Guards of the Vatican, or if they are dual citizens of a foreign country and reside there.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss militia system stipulates that soldiers keep their army-issued equipment, including fully automatic personal weapons, at home.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Men usually receive military conscription orders for training at the age of 18.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] About two-thirds of young Swiss are found suitable for service; for the others, various forms of alternative service are available.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Annually, approximately 20,000 persons are trained in recruit centres for 18 to 21 weeks.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The reform "Army XXI" was adopted by popular vote in 2003, replacing "Army 95", reducing the rolls from 400,000 to about 200,000.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Of those, 120,000 are active in periodic Army training, and 80,000 are non-training reserves.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The newest reform of the military, *Weiterentwicklung der Armee* (WEA; English: Further development of the Army), started in 2018 and was expected to reduce the number of army personnel to 100,000 by the end of 2022.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Overall, three general mobilisations have been declared to ensure the integrity and neutrality of Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The first mobilisation was held in response to the Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71; while the second was in response to the First World War outbreak in August 1914; the third mobilisation took place in September 1939 in response to the German attack on Poland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Because of its neutrality policy, the Swiss army does not take part in armed conflicts in other countries but joins some peacekeeping missions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Since 2000 the armed force department has maintained the Onyx intelligence gathering system to monitor satellite communications.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Gun politics in Switzerland are unique in Europe in that 2–3.5 million guns are in the hands of civilians, giving the nation an estimate of 28–41 guns per 100 people.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] As per the Small Arms Survey, only 324,484 guns are owned by the military.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Only 143,372 are in the hands of soldiers.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] However, ammunition is no longer issued.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has a stable, prosperous and high-tech economy.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is frequently ranked among the world's wealthiest country per capita; for example in 2024 the CIA world factbook ranked Switzerland as having the 10th highest GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in the world.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The country ranks as one of the least corrupt countries in the world, while its banking sector was rated in 2018 as "one of the most corrupt in the world".
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It has the world's twentieth largest economy by nominal GDP and the thirty-eighth largest by purchasing power parity.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] As of 2021, it is the thirteenth largest exporter, and the fifth largest per capita.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Zurich and Geneva are regarded as global cities, ranked as Alpha and Beta respectively.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Basel is the capital of Switzerland's pharmaceutical industry, hosting Novartis, Roche, and many other players.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is one of the world's most important centres for the life sciences industry.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland had the second-highest global rating in the Index of Economic Freedom 2023, while also providing significant public services.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] On a per capita basis, nominal GDP is higher than those of the larger Western and Central European economies and Japan, while adjusted for purchasing power, Switzerland ranked 11th in 2017, fifth in 2018, and ninth in 2020.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The European Union labelled Switzerland Europe's most innovative country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has been ranked the most innovative country in the Global Innovation Index in 2025, as it had done in 2024, 2023, 2022, 2021, 2020 and 2019.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It ranked 20th of 189 countries in the Ease of Doing Business Index.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland's slow growth in the 1990s and the early 2000s increased support for economic reforms and harmonisation with the European Union.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2020, IMD placed Switzerland first in attracting skilled workers.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] For much of the 20th century, Switzerland was the wealthiest country in Europe by a considerable margin (per capita GDP).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has one of the world's largest account balances as a percentage of GDP.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2018, the canton of Basel-City had the highest GDP per capita, ahead of Zug and Geneva.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] According to Credit Suisse, only about 37% of residents own their own homes, one of the lowest rates of home ownership in Europe.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Housing and food price levels were 171% and 145% of the EU-25 index in 2007, compared to 113% and 104% in Germany.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland is home to several large multinational corporations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The largest by revenue are Glencore, Gunvor, Nestlé, Mediterranean Shipping Company, Novartis, Hoffmann-La Roche, ABB, Mercuria Energy Group and Adecco.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Also, notable are UBS, Zurich Insurance, Richemont, Credit Suisse, Barry Callebaut, Swiss Re, Rolex, Tetra Pak, Swatch Group and Swiss International Air Lines.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland's most important economic sector is manufacturing.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Manufactured products include speciality chemicals, health and pharmaceutical goods, scientific and precision measuring instruments and musical instruments.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The largest exported goods are chemicals (34% of exported goods), machines/electronics (20.9%), and precision instruments/watches (16.9%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The service sector – especially banking and insurance, commodities trading, tourism, and international organisations – is another important industry for Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Exported services amount to a third of exports.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Agricultural protectionism—a rare exception to Switzerland's free trade policies—contributes to high food prices.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Product market liberalisation is lagging behind many EU countries according to the OECD.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Apart from agriculture, economic and trade barriers between the European Union and Switzerland are minimal, and Switzerland has free trade agreements with many countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland is a member of the European Free Trade Association (EFTA).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland is considered as the "land of Cooperatives" with the ten largest cooperative companies accounting for more than 11% of GDP in 2018.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] They include Migros and Coop, the two largest retail companies in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It features low tax rates; tax revenue to GDP ratio is one of the smallest of developed countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss Federal budget reached 62.8 billion Swiss francs in 2010, 11.35% of GDP; however, canton and municipality budgets are not counted as part of the federal budget.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Total government spending is closer to 33.8% of GDP.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The main sources of income for the federal government are the value-added tax (33% of tax revenue) and the direct federal tax (29%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The main areas of expenditure are in social welfare and finance/taxes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The expenditures of the Swiss Confederation have been growing from 7% of GDP in 1960 to 9.7% in 1990 and 10.7% in 2010.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] While the social welfare and finance sectors and tax grew from 35% in 1990 to 48.2% in 2010, a significant reduction of expenditures has been occurring in agriculture and national defence; from 26.5% to 12.4% (estimation for the year 2015).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Slightly more than 5 million people work in Switzerland; about 25% of employees belonged to a trade union in 2004.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has a more flexible labour market than neighbouring countries and the unemployment rate is consistently low.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The unemployment rate increased from 1.7% in June 2000 to 4.4% in December 2009.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It then decreased to 3.2% in 2014 and held steady for several years, before further dropping to 2.5% in 2018 and 2.3% in 2019; in 2023 it had reached a 20-year low of 2%.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Population growth (from net immigration) reached 0.52% of population in 2004, increased in the following years before falling to 0.54% again in 2017.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The foreign citizen population was 28.9% in 2015, about the same as in Australia.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2022, the median monthly gross income in Switzerland was 6,788 francs per month (equivalent to US$7,467 per month).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] After rent, taxes and pension contributions, plus spending on goods and services, the average household has about 15% of its gross income left for savings.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Though 61% of the population made less than the mean income, income inequality is relatively low with a Gini coefficient of 29.7, placing Switzerland among the top 20 countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2015, the richest 1% owned 35% of the wealth.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Wealth inequality increased through 2019.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] About 8.2% of the population live below the national poverty line, defined in Switzerland as earning less than CHF 3,990 per month for a household of two adults and two children, and a further 15% are at risk of poverty.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Single-parent families, those with no post-compulsory education and those out of work are among the most likely to live below the poverty line.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Although work is considered a way out of poverty, some 4.3% are considered working poor.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] One in ten jobs in Switzerland is considered low-paid; roughly 12% of Swiss workers hold such jobs, many of them women and foreigners.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland is among the countries with the highest number of Nobel laureates, both in total and per capita; of the 28 Swiss nationals who have won the Nobel Prize, 23 were recognised in the sciences.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Among the most famous is Albert Einstein, who became a Swiss citizen in 1901 and developed his theory of special relativity in Bern.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Among the Nobel laureates born or naturalised in Switzerland are Vladimir Prelog, Heinrich Rohrer, Richard Ernst, Edmond Fischer, Rolf Zinkernagel, Kurt Wüthrich and Jacques Dubochet.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Over 100 laureates across all fields have a relationship to Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Nobel Peace Prize has been awarded nine times to organisations headquartered in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Geneva and the nearby French department of Ain co-host the world's largest laboratory, CERN, dedicated to particle physics research.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Another important research centre is the Paul Scherrer Institute, which conducts multi-disciplinary research in the natural and engineering sciences.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Notable Swiss inventions include lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD), diazepam (Valium), Velcro, and the scanning tunnelling microscope, which earned inventors Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer the 1986 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Auguste Piccard became the first person to enter the Stratosphere with his pressurised hydrogen ballon, while his son Jacques Piccard became one of the first people to explore the deepest known part of the world's ocean (along with American Don Walsh).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss Space Office has been involved in various space technologies and programmes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It was one of the 10 founders of the European Space Agency in 1975 and is the seventh largest contributor to the ESA budget.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In the private sector, several companies participate in the space industry, such as Oerlikon Space and Maxon Motors.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Electricity generated in Switzerland is 56% from hydroelectricity and 39% from nuclear power, producing negligible CO2.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] On 18 May 2003, two anti-nuclear referendums were defeated: *Moratorium Plus*, aimed at forbidding the building of new nuclear power plants (41.6% supported), and Electricity Without Nuclear (33.7% supported) after a moratorium expired in 2000.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] After the Fukushima nuclear disaster, in 2011 the government announced plans to end the use of nuclear energy in the following 20 to 30 years.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In November 2016, Swiss voters rejected a Green Party referendum to accelerate the phaseout of nuclear power (45.8% supported).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss Federal Office of Energy (SFOE) is responsible for energy supply and energy use within the Federal Department of Environment, Transport, Energy and Communications (DETEC).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The agency supports the 2000-watt society initiative to cut the nation's energy use by more than half by 2050.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland had approximately 6,562,600 motor vehicles (excluding mopeds) in 2025.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The largest category was passenger cars with 4,829,500 units (58.7% running on petrol, 24% on diesel, 5.2% on electricity and 11.9% hybrid).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The densest rail network in Europe spans 5,250 kilometres (3,260 mi) and carried 614 million passengers in 2023.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2023, each Swiss resident travelled on average 2,446 kilometres (1,520 mi) by rail, more than any other European country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Virtually 100% of the network is electrified.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] 60% of the network is operated by the Swiss Federal Railways (SBB CFF FFS).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland operates the world's longest and deepest railway tunnel and the first flat, low-level route through the Alps, the 57.1-kilometre-long (35.5 mi) Gotthard Base Tunnel, the largest part of the New Railway Link through the Alps (NRLA) project.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] For example, a 2010 microcensus discovered that in Zurich, Switzerland's largest city, 32% of its inhabitants use the city's public transport regularly (trams or trolleybuses, of which 60% used at least those two modes), while 26% depended on a personal vehicle.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Fewer than half the residents owned a car or a motorcycle.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has a publicly managed, toll-free road network financed by highway permits as well as vehicle and petrol taxes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss autobahn/autoroute system requires the annual purchase of a vignette (toll sticker)—for 40 Swiss francs—to use its roadways, including passenger cars and trucks.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss autobahn/autoroute network stretches for 2,259 km (1,404 mi) and has one of the highest motorway densities in the world.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Zurich Airport is Switzerland's largest international flight gateway; it handled 31.2 million passengers in 2024.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The other international airports are Geneva Airport (13.9 million passengers in 2012), EuroAirport Basel Mulhouse Freiburg (located in France), Bern Airport, Lugano Airport, St.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Gallen-Altenrhein Airport and Sion Airport.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Swiss International Air Lines is the flag carrier.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Its main hub is Zurich, but it is legally domiciled in Basel.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In November 2025, Switzerland's Federal Roads Office (FEDRO) granted WeRide, a global leader in autonomous driving technology, a driverless permit which authorises it to operate autonomously on public roads in the Furttal region.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] This is the first driverless Robotaxi permit for passengers issued in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has one of the best environmental records among developed nations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is a signatory to the Kyoto Protocol; alongside Mexico and South Korea, it was a founding member of the Environmental Integrity Group (EIG).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The country is active in recycling and anti-littering programs and is one of the world's top recyclers, recovering 66% to 96% of recyclable materials, varying across the country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The 2014 Global Green Economy Index placed Switzerland among the top 10 green economies.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has an economic system for garbage disposal, which is based mostly on recycling and energy-producing incinerators.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] As in other European countries, the illegal disposal of garbage is heavily fined.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In almost all Swiss municipalities, mandatory stickers or dedicated garbage bags allow the identification of disposable garbage.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss population is about 9 million as of June 2024.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Like other developed countries, Switzerland experienced rapid population growth during the industrial era, with the number of inhabitants quadrupling between 1800 and 1990.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Population growth is projected to continue to 2035, due mostly to immigration.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Like most of Europe, Switzerland faces an ageing population, with a fertility rate close to replacement level.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has one of the world's oldest populations, with an average age of 44.5 years.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] According to the World Factbook, as of 2020, the largest ethnic group in the country is Swiss (69.2%), which includes several ethno-linguistic groups, followed by German (4.2%), Italian (3.2%), Portuguese (2.5%), French (2.1%), Kosovan (1.1%), Turkish (1%), and other (16.7%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Council of Europe suggests a population of around 30,000 Romani people.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2023, resident foreigners made up 26.3% of Switzerland's population.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Most of these (83%) were from European countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Immigrants from Sri Lanka (1.3%), most of them former Tamil refugees, were the largest group of Asian origin (7.9%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] 2021 figures show that 39.5% (compared to 34.7% in 2012) of the permanent resident population aged 15 or over (around 2.89 million), had an immigrant background.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] 38% of the population with an immigrant background (1.1 million) held Swiss citizenship.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In the 2000s, domestic and international institutions expressed concern about what was perceived as an increase in xenophobia.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In reply to one critical report, the Federal Council noted that "racism unfortunately is present in Switzerland", but stated that the high proportion of foreign citizens in the country, as well as the generally successful integration of foreigners, underlined Switzerland's openness.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] A follow-up study conducted in 2018 reported that 59% considered racism a serious problem in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The proportion of the population that claimed to have been targeted by racial discrimination increased from 10% in 2014 to almost 17% in 2018, according to the Federal Statistical Office.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has four national languages: mainly German (spoken natively by 62% of the population in 2026); French (22.7%) spoken natively in the west; and Italian (8.2%) spoken natively in the south.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The fourth national language, Romansh (0.5%), is a Romance language spoken locally in the southeastern trilingual canton of Grisons, and is designated by Article 4 of the Federal Constitution as a national language along with German, French, and Italian.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In Article 70 it is mentioned as an official language if the authorities communicate with persons who speak Romansh.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] However, federal laws and other official acts do not need to be decreed in Romansh.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2016, the languages most spoken at home among permanent residents aged 15 and older were Swiss German (59.4%), French (23.5%), Standard German (10.6%), and Italian (8.5%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Other languages spoken at home included English (5.0%), Portuguese (3.8%), Albanian (3.0%), Spanish (2.6%) and Serbian and Croatian (2.5%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] 6.9% reported speaking another language at home.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2019 more than two-thirds (68%) of the permanent resident population indicated speaking more than one language regularly.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The federal government is obliged to communicate in the official languages, and in the federal parliament simultaneous translation is provided from and into German, French and Italian.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Aside from the official forms of their respective languages, the four linguistic regions of Switzerland also have local dialectal forms.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The principal official languages have terms not used outside of Switzerland, known as Helvetisms.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] German Helvetisms are, roughly speaking, a large group of words typical of Swiss Standard German that do not appear in Standard German, nor in other German dialects.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] These include terms from Switzerland's surrounding language cultures (German *Billett* from French), from similar terms in another language (Italian *azione* used not only as *act* but also as *discount* from German *Aktion*).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Swiss French, while generally close to the French of France, also contains some Helvetisms.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The most frequent characteristics of Helvetisms are in vocabulary, phrases, and pronunciation, although certain Helvetisms denote themselves as special in syntax and orthography.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Duden, the comprehensive German dictionary, contains about 3000 Helvetisms.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Current French dictionaries, such as the Petit Larousse, include several hundred Helvetisms; notably, Swiss French uses different terms than that of France for the numbers 70 (*septante*) and 90 (*nonante*) and often 80 (*huitante*) as well.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Learning one of the other national languages is compulsory for all Swiss pupils, hence many Swiss are supposed to be at least bilingual, especially those belonging to linguistic minority groups.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Because the largest part of Switzerland is German-speaking, many French, Italian, and Romansh speakers migrating to the rest of Switzerland and the children of those non-German-speaking Swiss born within the rest of Switzerland speak German.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] While learning one of the other national languages at school is important, most Swiss learn English to communicate with Swiss speakers of other languages, as it is perceived as a neutral means of communication.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] English often functions as the *de facto* lingua franca.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Christianity is the predominant religion according to national surveys of Swiss Federal Statistical Office, divided between the Catholic Church (31.9% of the population), the Swiss Reformed Church (20.4%) and other Christian denominations.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland has no official state religion, though most cantons (except Geneva and Neuchâtel) recognise official churches, either the Catholic Church or the Swiss Reformed Church.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] These churches, and in some cantons the Old Catholic Church and Jewish congregations, are financed by official taxation of members.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2020, the Roman Catholic Church had 3,048,475 registered and church tax paying members (corresponding to 35.2% of the total population), while the Swiss Reformed Church had 2,015,816 members (23.3% of the total population).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Close to one-third (33.8%) of the population are not affiliated with a religious community.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] By 2024, half the Swiss population never attended a religious event in the 12 months preceding, according to the Federal Statistical Office.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] More than a quarter who left their religion cite loss of faith or disagreement with their religious community.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Education in Switzerland is diverse, because the constitution of Switzerland delegates the operation for the school system to the cantons.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Public and private schools are available, including many private international schools.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The minimum age for primary school is about six years, but most cantons provide a free "children's school" starting at age four or five.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Primary school continues until grade four, five or six, depending on the school.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Traditionally, the first foreign language in school was one of the other Swiss languages, although in 2000, English was elevated in a few cantons.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] At the end of primary school or at the beginning of secondary school, pupils are assigned according to their capacities into one of several sections (often three).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The fastest learners are taught advanced classes to prepare for further studies and the matura, while other students receive an education adapted to their needs.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Switzerland hosts 12 universities, ten of which are maintained at cantonal level and usually offer non-technical subjects.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It ranked 87th on the 2019 Academic Ranking of World Universities.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The largest is the University of Zurich with nearly 25,000 students.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Swiss Federal Institute of Technology Zurich (ETHZ) and the University of Zurich are listed 20th and 54th respectively, on the 2015 Academic Ranking of World Universities.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The federal government sponsors two institutes: the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology Zurich (ETHZ) in Zurich, founded in 1855 and the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) in Lausanne, founded in 1969, formerly associated with the University of Lausanne.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Eight of the world's ten best hotel schools are located in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In addition, various universities of applied sciences are available.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In business and management studies, the University of St.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies, located in Geneva, is continental Europe's oldest graduate school of international and development studies.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] It is widely held to be one of its most prestigious.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Swiss residents are required to buy health insurance from private insurance companies, which in turn are required to accept every applicant.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] While the cost of the system is among the highest, its health outcomes compare well with other European countries; patients have been reported as in general, highly satisfied with it.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] In 2022, life expectancy at birth was 82.2 years for men and 85.8 years for women.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Spending on health at 11.7% of GDP (2022) is about on par with Germany and France (12.7%, 12.1%), but higher than many other European countries (Italy: 9.0%, Norway: 7.9%, Ireland: 6.1%), but notably less than the US (16.6%).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] From 1990, costs more or less steadily increased.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p02] Issues relating to health include high drugs consumption, smoking and mental illness".
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Swiss culture is characterised by diversity, which is reflected in diverse traditional customs.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] A region may be in some ways culturally connected to the neighbouring country that shares its language, all rooted in western European culture.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The linguistically isolated Romansh culture in Graubünden in eastern Switzerland constitutes an exception.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] It survives only in the upper valleys of the Rhine and the Inn and strives to maintain its rare linguistic tradition.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Switzerland is home to notable contributors to art, architecture, literature, music and sciences.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] In addition, the country attracted creatives during times of unrest or war.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Some 1000 museums are found in the country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Among the most important cultural performances held annually are the Paléo Festival, Lucerne Festival, the Montreux Jazz Festival, the Locarno International Film Festival and Art Basel.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] In addition, Switzerland has hosted the Eurovision Song Contest thrice, in 1956 (the inaugural edition, held in Lugano), 1989 (Lausanne), and 2025 (Basel), and won three times, through Lys Assia in 1956, Celine Dion in 1988, and Nemo in 2024.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Alpine symbolism played an essential role in shaping Swiss history and the Swiss national identity.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Many alpine areas and ski resorts attract visitors for winter sports as well as hiking and mountain biking in summer.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The quieter seasons are spring and autumn.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] A traditional pastoral culture predominates in many areas, and small farms are omnipresent in rural areas.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Folk art is nurtured in organisations across the country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Switzerland most directly in appears in music, dance, poetry, wood carving, and embroidery.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The alphorn, a trumpet-like musical instrument made of wood has joined yodelling and the accordion as epitomes of traditional Swiss music.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The earliest forms of literature were in German, reflecting the language's early predominance.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] In the 18th century, French became fashionable in Bern and elsewhere, while the influence of the French-speaking allies and subject lands increased.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Among the classic authors of Swiss literature are Jeremias Gotthelf (1797–1854) and Gottfried Keller (1819–1890); later writers are Max Frisch (1911–1991) and Friedrich Dürrenmatt (1921–1990), whose *Das Versprechen* (*The Pledge*) was released as a Hollywood film in 2001, starring Jack Nicholson.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Famous French-speaking writers were Jean-Jacques Rousseau (1712–1778) and Germaine de Staël (1766–1817).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] More recent authors include Charles Ferdinand Ramuz (1878–1947), whose novels describe the lives of peasants and mountain dwellers, set in a harsh environment, and Blaise Cendrars (born Frédéric Sauser, 1887–1961).
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Italian and Romansh-speaking authors also contributed to the Swiss literary landscape, generally in proportion to their number.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Probably the most famous Swiss literary creation, *Heidi*, the story of an orphan girl who lives with her grandfather in the Alps, is one of the most popular children's books and has come to be a symbol of Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Her creator, Johanna Spyri (1827–1901), wrote a number of books on similar themes.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Freedom of the press and the right to free expression is guaranteed in the constitution.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The Swiss News Agency (SNA) broadcasts information in three of the four national languages—on politics, economics, society and culture.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The SNA supplies almost all Swiss media and foreign media with its reporting.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] In Switzerland, the most influential newspapers include the German-language *Tages-Anzeiger* and *Neue Zürcher Zeitung*, as well as the French-language *Le Temps*.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Additionally, almost every city has at least one local newspaper published in the predominant local language.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The government exerts greater control over broadcast media than print media, especially due to financing and licensing.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The Swiss Broadcasting Corporation, an EBU member, whose name was recently changed to SRG SSR, is charged with the production and distribution of radio and television content.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] SRG SSR studios are distributed across the various language regions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Radio content is produced in six central and four regional studios while video media are produced in Geneva, Zurich, Basel, and Lugano.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] An extensive cable network allows most Swiss to access content from neighbouring countries.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] While dishes such as fondue, raclette or rösti are omnipresent, each region developed its gastronomy according to the varieties of climate and language, for example, *Zürcher Geschnetzeltes*, engl.: sliced meat Zurich style.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Traditional Swiss cuisine uses ingredients similar to those in other European countries, as well as unique dairy products and cheeses such as Gruyère or Emmental, produced in the valleys of Gruyères and Emmental.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The number of fine-dining establishments is high, particularly in western Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Chocolate has been made in Switzerland since the 18th century.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Its reputation grew at the end of the 19th century with the invention of modern techniques such as conching and tempering, which enabled higher quality.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Another breakthrough was the invention of solid milk chocolate in 1875 by Daniel Peter.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The Swiss are the world's largest chocolate consumers.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The most popular alcoholic drink is wine.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Switzerland is notable for its variety of grape varieties, reflecting the large variations in terroirs.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Swiss wine is produced mainly in Valais, Vaud (Lavaux), Geneva and Ticino, with a small majority of white wines.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Vineyards have been cultivated in Switzerland since the Roman era, even though traces of a more ancient origin can be found.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The most widespread varieties are the Chasselas (called Fendant in Valais) and Pinot Noir.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Merlot is the main variety produced in Ticino.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Eighty-two percent of the population regularly drinks alcoholic beverages.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Skiing, snowboarding and mountaineering are among the most popular sports, reflecting the nature of the country.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Winter sports are practised by natives and visitors.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The first world ski championships were held in Mürren (1931) and St.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The latter town hosted the second Winter Olympic Games in 1928 and the fifth edition in 1948.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Among its most successful skiers and world champions are Pirmin Zurbriggen and Didier Cuche.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The most prominently watched sports in Switzerland are football and ice hockey.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The headquarters of the international football's and ice hockey's governing bodies, the International Federation of Association Football (FIFA) and International Ice Hockey Federation (IIHF) are located in Zurich.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Many other headquarters of international sports federations are located in Switzerland.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] For example, the International Olympic Committee (IOC), IOC's Olympic Museum and the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) are located in Lausanne.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Switzerland hosted the 1954 FIFA World Cup and was the joint host, with Austria, of the UEFA Euro 2008 tournament.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The Swiss Super League is the nation's professional football club league, with clubs including BSC Young Boys performing consistently in European club competitions.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Europe's highest football pitch, at 2,000 metres (6,600 ft) above sea level, is located in Switzerland, the *Ottmar Hitzfeld Stadium*.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Many Swiss follow ice hockey and support one of the 14 teams of the National League, which is the most attended league in Europe.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] In 2009, Switzerland hosted the IIHF World Championship for the tenth time.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] It also became World Vice-Champion in 2013, 2018 and 2024.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Its numerous lakes make Switzerland an attractive sailing destination.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The largest, Lake Geneva, is the home of the sailing team Alinghi which was the first European team to win the America's Cup in 2003 and which successfully defended the title in 2007.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Swiss tennis player Roger Federer is widely regarded as among the sport's greatest players.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] He won 20 Grand Slam tournaments overall including a record 8 Wimbledon titles.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] 1 in the ATP rankings for a record 237 consecutive weeks.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Fellow Swiss players Martina Hingis and Stan Wawrinka also won multiple Grand Slam titles.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Switzerland won the Davis Cup title in 2014.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Motorsport racecourses and events were banned in Switzerland following the 1955 Le Mans disaster with exceptions for events such as hillclimbing.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The country continued to produce successful racing drivers such as Clay Regazzoni, Sébastien Buemi, Jo Siffert, Dominique Aegerter, successful World Touring Car Championship driver Alain Menu, 2014 24 Hours of Le Mans winner Marcel Fässler and 2015 24 Hours Nürburgring winner Nico Müller.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Switzerland also won the A1GP World Cup of Motorsport in 2007–08 with driver Neel Jani.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Swiss motorcycle racer Thomas Lüthi won the 2005 MotoGP World Championship in the 125cc category.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] The ban was ultimately lifted in May 2022, on the grounds that safety in motorsport had vastly improved since the ban was first imposed.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] However, despite the ban being lifted in 2022, Motorsport will officially be legalised on June 1, 2026, meaning Motorsport will be legal for the first time in 71 years.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Traditional sports include Swiss wrestling or *Schwingen*, a tradition from the rural central cantons and considered the national sport by some.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Hornussen is another indigenous Swiss sport, which is like a cross between baseball and golf.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] *Steinstossen* is the Swiss variant of stone put, a competition in throwing a heavy stone.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] Practised only among the alpine population since prehistoric times, it is recorded to have taken place in Basel in the 13th century.
[src:switzerland/switzerland-p03] It is central to the Unspunnenfest, first held in 1805, with its symbol the 83.5 stone named *Unspunnenstein*.
